<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 28 日星期五 12:12:02 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[When Judaism Went à la Carte]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>纪念<em>《犹太目录》</em>出版 50 周年<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/6s7RTp_ci5XzjucdbQH2TUthYtY=/0x0:2160x2700/648x810/media/img/2023/07/27/jewish_catalog_/original.jpg" alt="《犹太目录》封面" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔安妮·因佩里奥/大西洋月刊。资料来源：美国犹太出版协会/互联网档案馆。</figcaption></figure> <span class="smallcaps">20 世纪 70 年代<span style="font-variant-caps: normal; letter-spacing: normal; text-transform: none;">初</span>，</span>美国犹太人总体上是中间派和传统派。大多数人都结婚了，而且大多数都与其他犹太人结婚了。他们最大的宗教派别是保守派运动，其郊区的犹太教堂平淡而宽敞，代表着陈旧传统和全面改革之间的中间立场。这个社区似乎已经适应了一种舒适的现状，在战后稳步同化并跻身中产阶级。<br><br>尽管如此，有迹象表明，当涉及到实际的宗教实践时，20 世纪 60 年代成熟的年轻一代发现这种稳定令人窒息。从底层可以感受到变革的渴望。 1972年，第一位女性拉比被任命。三分之二 30 岁以下的犹太人根本不属于任何犹太教堂。但在波士顿、纽约和华盛顿特区等城市，一群年轻、受过良好教育的犹太人开始非正式地一起崇拜和学习，避开机构监督和父母的顺从。<br><br>在波士顿郊外一个名为 Havurat Shalom 的公共聚会上，三名 20 多岁的年轻人决定制作一本不同于任何人见过的宗教书籍：一本生动的、众包的概要，讲述如何过犹太人的生活。它通过反主流文化的敏感性重新构想了古代仪式，挑战了右翼传统主义者和左翼改良主义者。右翼传统主义者的意识形态将犹太教视为严格的、包罗万象的规则和期望，而左翼改良主义者在很大程度上拒绝仪式，因为它要求不那么高，不太明显的宗教身份。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-first-jewish-catalog-richard-siegel/9780827600423?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《犹太目录》</i></a>于 1973 年由犹太出版协会出版，意外成为畅销书，并一直印刷至今——今年，它庆祝了它的 50 周年纪念。只有 JPS 的圣经译本为出版商卖出了更多的副本。<i>该目录</i>的鲜红色封面、独特的设计和异想天开的插图使几代犹太人能够尝试新的实践和社区形式，成为那些疏远传统并寻求更有意义的替代方案的人的终极手册。今天，当有组织的宗教受到骚乱和脱离的困扰时， <i>《目录》</i>成为了一个案例研究，说明草根宗教生活现代化的努力如何能够以深刻而持久的方式取得成功，尽管多年来仍然存在一个问题，即其变革的可持续性如何实际上是。<br><br>这<span class="smallcaps">本 320 页的书及其</span>两部续集是在 20 世纪 60 年代的社会动荡和政治暴力让位于出版业中以“自己动手”的反主流文化为代表的《全球概览<i>》（Whole Earth Catalog）</i>中出现的。实用资源颂扬自给自足。尽管<i>《犹太目录》</i>一开始是《<i>全球目录》</i>的犹太版本，但当其编辑理查德·西格尔、迈克尔·斯特拉斯菲尔德和莎朗·斯特拉斯菲尔德与 JPS 签约时，他们已经创造了更具革命性的东西。<br><br>在他们开始他们的项目之前，约瑟夫·卡罗 (Joseph Caro) 在 16 世纪撰写了描述如何过犹太人生活的经典文本：《 <i>Shulchan Aruch》</i> ，字面意思是“固定的桌子”，是一套已确立的、广泛接受的犹太法典。相比之下， <i>《犹太目录》</i>提供了点菜菜单，鼓励读者为自己创造一个灵活、非正式和积极主动的犹太教。想遵守安息日，但祈祷和律法没有共鸣？您只想每周烤一次白面包吗？好吧，这里有一两个食谱，还有手绘的几种编织仪式面包的方法。<br><br> “你可以在任何你想要的地方插入，”编辑在简介中写道。<br><br>哈伊姆·波托克（Chaim Potok）当时是一位以<i>《选民》</i>而闻名的著名小说家，他是 JPS 的最高编辑，尽管他立即意识到了<i>《目录》</i>的潜力，但他在董事会的一些成员中遇到了困难，他们对出版如此非传统的、有时是不敬的工作。但他坚持了下来。 “哈伊姆是一位有远见的人，”莎朗·斯特拉斯菲尔德告诉我。<br><br>当时，施特拉斯菲尔德夫妇（后来结婚）和西格尔（于 2018 年去世）是 Havurat Shalom 的成员，这是一个由外行领导的社区，是平等、参与式崇拜、学习和仪式实践形式的先驱之一。<i>该目录</i>反映了这些价值观。 “我们正在写我们的生活，”莎朗·斯特拉斯菲尔德说。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/03/orthodox-judaism-millennials/476118/">阅读：为什么正统犹太教吸引如此多的千禧一代</a><br><br><i>《目录》</i>的编辑明确批评传统犹太教是“预制的、填鸭式的、近视的”。他们甚至将其中一章命名为“利用犹太机构——一个不情愿的指南”。<br><br>但总体而言，语气和表达方式是有趣的、包容的、肯定的。模糊的照片中，赤脚男女紧握双手、跳圈舞，与婚礼上极端正统的新娘和新郎并列；一页是长发嬉皮士，另一页是长胡子哈西德派。在 Adrianne Onderdonk Dudden 的设计中，页面具有塔木德风格，评论和解释围绕着正文。斯图·科潘斯 (Stu Copans) 迷人的线条画既有启发性，又很厚颜无耻。社论也是如此。 （<i>胆汁</i>汤是一种长时间炖煮的炖菜，食谱上说它可以喂饱 10 个正常人或两个匈牙利人。）<br><br> “我不认为我们想把它强加给这个人，”迈克尔·斯特拉斯菲尔德告诉我。 “我们以一种非常不同的方式看待犹太人的生活，这本书就是这种方式的表达。犹太人的组织生活很无聊。郊区的犹太人生活很无聊。我们试图连接到更真实的过去——试图重新夺回某些东西，而不是破坏系统。我们想提供另一种模式。”<br><br>这种模式散发出更广泛的青年文化的无忧无虑的快乐和非传统。为什么祈祷披肩必须只有黑色和白色？为什么它们不能是多彩的？为什么女性就不能穿它们呢？<br><br> “这是一种观念，即你可以做到这一点，你可以拥有它，”宾夕法尼亚大学历史学教授贝丝·温格告诉我。 “你不需要去某个机构来做这件事。是你的。这就是如此有影响力的地方。”<br><br><span class="smallcaps">没有任何大规模营销</span>可言，主要依靠口碑和<i>《纽约时报》的</i>报道， <i>《目录》</i>的第一版印刷品立即售罄，前三个月销售了 50,000 份，18 个月内销售了 130,000 份。 （虽然 JPS 表示总销量有数十万，但没有最新的数据。）<br><br>对于像 JPS 这样的小众出版商来说，这些数字是前所未有的。但这种流行并非没有争议。<br><br>最引人注目的是当时美国杰出的犹太社区生活社会学家马歇尔·斯克莱尔 (Marshall Sklare) 在<i>《评论》</i>杂志 1974 年 12 月号上发表的一篇冗长、严厉的文章。这篇文章的标题是“犹太教的绿化”——这并不是一种恭维——<i>批评目录</i>编辑们“让自己免受犹太宗教法的核心特征——其规范性”的影响。<br><br>斯克莱尔总结说，<i>这本目录</i>“充满了讽刺意味，在这部作品中，对犹太来源和犹太习俗的真正熟悉被用来服务于最新的文化和审美偏好，其结果是有趣的、粗俗的、迷人的和一下子就变得光荣了。”<br><br>撇开撕裂、贬低的语气，斯克莱尔指出了一个核心事实： <i>《目录》</i>确实在推进一种注重美、意义和个人体验的犹太教，而不是公共义务和屈服于等级制度和权威。你被邀请以某种方式行动和思考，而不是被命令这样做。<br><br>但是，如果说<i>《目录》</i>挑战了右翼盛行的正统观念，那么它也是对美国左翼犹太教的含蓄谴责，尤其是广受欢迎的改革运动，该运动当时避开了宗教仪式和公开展示种族，转而支持一种更自由的宗教仪式。类似新教的道德，有许多用英语进行的祈祷，仪式也比较简短，几乎没有空间表达祈祷的情感。<br><br> 50 年前， <i>《目录》</i>所阐述的内容已经从美国犹太教自由派甚至一些较为保守派别的边缘走向了主流。如今，犹太教堂的崇拜总体上不再那么正式，而更具参与性。仪式行为不断被重新发明。平等主义已经渗透到现代正统观念中。而且，在大流行的推动下，似乎所有其他犹太家庭都在为安息日制作白面包。<br><br>贝丝·温格指出，更广泛地说， <i>《目录》</i>的观点“是美国宗教的特征，今天它主要是一份菜单。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/08/zohar-kabbalah-mainstream-judaism/537621/">阅读：将卡巴拉恢复为犹太教主流</a><br><br>也许即使是马歇尔·斯克莱尔（Marshall Sklare）（如果他还活着）也不会质疑<i>《犹太目录》</i>对美国犹太教产生的深刻而持久的影响。但这本似乎每个人书架上都有的大书现在基本上成了一件受人喜爱的历史文物。互联网在一毫秒内提供了<i>《目录</i>》作者花费数年时间编写的内容。本来应该成为资源的书籍在付印的那一刻就立即过时了。 <i>《目录》</i>中列出学者、参考文献和组织的精美章节现在已经过时了。<br><br>传统的知识和指导守门人——无论是拉比还是其他专家——在许多人生的戏剧中几乎扮演不了配角的角色。这主要是由于技术进步，但也是因为宗教机构在美国犹太人乃至许多其他美国人日常生活中的重要性下降。<br><br>无论<i>《目录》</i>引发还是催化了这一发展，无论它改变了美国犹太教的方向，还是生动地表达了已经在发生的转变，如果没有这本古怪、超大的书进行实验的许可，很难想象当代美国犹太人的生活。代表。<br><br> “我们所做的最具颠覆性的事情，而且完全是无意的，就是我们为人们提供了英语工具，以便他们能够建立自己的犹太人生活，”莎朗·斯特拉斯菲尔德说。 “在那之前，谁在写一本犹太书？拉比和学者。<i>该目录</i>的全部目的是让他们自己的犹太教人民拥有所有权。”<br><br>作为一本书， <i>《目录</i>》的起源故事具备了成功的所有要素：理想主义和知识渊博的编辑，有远见的出版商，颠覆的时机已经成熟。但为了真正激发一场重塑宗教生活的运动，这本书还要求读者具备接受其 DIY 精神的技能、热情和承诺。真正拥有自己的宗教信仰并对其可持续性负责需要付出大量的努力。半个世纪过去了， <i>《目录》</i>的贡献依然存在，但让信仰在现代世界中变得有意义和新鲜的挥之不去的挑战也同样存在。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/the-jewish-catalog-50th-anniversary/674846/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/the-jewish-catalog-50th-anniversary/674846/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Inside the Israeli Crack-Up]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在这里生活了 30 年之后，我对以色列有了一些新的认识。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/BmhCzSvXcdVITJeiy3c4J7VQvBg=/0x0:5076x2855/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/AP23205574760473/original.jpg" alt="照片显示以色列示威者。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>奥哈德·茨维根贝格/美联社</figcaption></figure>过去六个月里，以色列感觉就像一座疯人院，一场规模相当于新泽西州的政治抗议，无休止的交通堵塞，坏想法的实验室，社交媒体时代西方民主未来的一瞥。它也是一间教室，即使对于我们这些自认为是专家的人来说也是如此。我在这里生活和写作了近30年。但周一，当我站在议会外的数千名抗议者中时，中午的炎热天气让我几乎渴望得到警察高压水枪的帮助，我意识到我正在学习用新的眼光来看待这个国家。<br><br>在以色列议会内部，以色列历史上最极端的政府正在立法其计划的第一阶段，将权力从法院转移到自己手中，从而改变民主游戏规则。法律通过了。抗议无法阻止它。一位反对派议员<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/Ram_Ben_Barak/status/1683437467515461635">形容</a>这是他一生中最艰难的一天，他曾经是摩萨德的二号人物。和这里的许多人一样，自今年年初以来，我几乎每周都会参加示威活动。这个人同样高喊着口号，挥舞着旗帜，但看起来很绝望，暗流中更多的是恐惧，而不是反抗。以色列历史的一个篇章即将结束。我们不知道接下来会发生什么。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-supreme-court-netanyahu-parliament/674833/">亚伊尔·罗森伯格：以色列已经输了</a><br><br>以色列对 2023 年的崩溃让该国以及我自己的假设和盲点变得更加清晰。<br><br> 1948 年 5 月 14 日，在阿拉伯世界联军的攻击下，以色列仓促宣布建国。那天特拉维夫的独立宣言承诺“不迟于 10 月 1 日”制定宪法，但我们从未抽出时间去做。相反，我们依赖的是权宜之计、当时看来合乎逻辑的政治协议，以及不成文的行事方式。以色列的团结与其说是通过法律，不如说是通过习俗。和许多以色列人一样，我意识到了这一点，但没有意识到其中的风险。这些习俗在生效时几乎是看不见的。他们现在可以看得清楚了，因为他们已经走了。<br><br>例如，按照惯例，总理如果面临起诉就辞职。按照惯例，不让罪犯负责执法。人们习惯于尊重公务员，听取在危险地区保护以色列人安全的士兵和间谍的意见，并且绝不将司法政治化。<br><br>最后一个规范与其他规范一起被现任政府抛弃，是我们麻烦的核心。在以色列制度中，简单多数的权力不受官方限制。因此，最高法院演变成了对国家的监督，用法律工具保护公民权利并打击腐败，而这些法律工具本身就具有临时性。但今年年初，总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡(Benjamin Netanyahu)的新政府在获得了不到49%的民众选票后，宣布了一项“法律改革”，该改革将削弱法院的作用，从而取消对政府权力的唯一制度性制约。内塔尼亚胡在选举前并未提出这一计划。新闻发布会带着宣战的语气。如果没有司法审查，政府可以推迟选举，取缔反对党，扩大神职人员的权力，并任命被判腐败罪的官员。 （所有这些想法都是由他的联盟成员提出的。）<br><br>事实始终是，议会中的多数人只需投票就可以摆脱一切限制。事实证明，唯一的障碍是对规范的习惯尊重。只要我们都相信它们，这些就存在，而它们缺失所留下的空白现在被怀疑和抗议所填补。<br><br>上周末，数万人举着以色列国旗沿着从特拉维夫到耶路撒冷的高速公路游行。在我撰写本文时，以色列议会附近的一个公园里布满了抗议者的帐篷。当我在营地时，志愿者团队正在制作食物并分发水瓶。举着旗帜的团体正步行上山前往议会外的抗议区，而其他人则红着脸、声音嘶哑地下山，在树荫下休息。那些在这黑暗的一年里寻找灵感的人已经在这场非同寻常的动员中找到了灵感，自一月份以来的每周，这种动员不是在 Facebook 上而是在街上发生。没有人，尤其是政府，预见到它的到来。这就提出了一个问题：到目前为止，每个人都在哪里。毕竟，自2009年以来，内塔尼亚胡和右翼一直掌权，只短暂休息过。<br><br>简短的答案是，在科技领域和度假领域。上世纪90年代末和20世纪初期，巴勒斯坦的自杀式爆炸和火箭弹摧毁了以色列的政治左派，在经济繁荣时期，以色列中产阶级的自由派人士追求繁荣，常常发现繁荣，但却陷入了政治沉睡。与此同时，定居者运动及其同情者正在努力在国家机构中获得权力，并利用犹太传统和对以色列创始人梦想的自由国家的敌意语言，与利库德集团和极端正统政党结成联盟。<br><br>自由派以色列人坚持他们对定居点的旧假设，即定居点是临时的，不属于以色列国，而定居者都是边缘怪人。他们认为内塔尼亚胡的基本目标是为公民实现和平与繁荣 — — 与他们的目标相同，也就是说，即使他以他们不喜欢的方式追求这一目标。<br><br>这些假设已经被现在掌权的人打破了。负责警察的部长伊塔马尔·本-格维尔（Itamar Ben-Gvir）和财政部长贝扎莱·斯莫特里奇（Bezalel Smotrich）也控制着部分国防部，他们都来自弥赛亚定居者运动，该运动有着完全不同的目标：犹太人统治整个土地以色列和一个受某种形式的宗教法管辖的国家。正是这种意识形态驱使 1995 年刺杀总理伊扎克·拉宾 (Yitzhak Rabin) 和 1994 年希伯伦大规模屠杀穆斯林信徒的巴鲁克·戈尔茨坦 (Baruch Goldstein)，直到最近，本·格维尔 (Ben-Gvir) 的客厅墙上还挂着他的照片。<br><br>对于这种极端因素来说，战争并不是不惜一切代价避免的恐怖，而是一种有理由推进上帝计划的考验，或者是在时机成熟时甚至可能是可取的事件。作为内阁部长，他们被赋予了帮助发动战争的潜在权力，无论是驱逐耶路撒冷的巴勒斯坦居民，还是对圣殿山的穆斯林圣地进行挑衅。对于头脑冷静、身着军装的以色列人以及青少年面临征兵的父母来说，这简直就是噩梦。<br><br>当以色列人被迫意识到定居者不仅不会前往西岸的任何地方，而且他们也不会去往任何地方时，抗议活动就爆发了。他们已经承担了以色列政府的核心职能，并正在迅速采取行动，消除对其权力的唯一限制。随着最高法院的退出，国家的转型将成为可能。这些都是利害关系，它们有助于解释我们所看到的愤怒和恐惧的激增，特别是包括飞行员和指挥人员在内的数千名预备役军人异常宣布他们将拒绝报到。这与其说是一种精心策划的施压策略，不如说是一种痛苦的嚎叫。如果六年前我没有因年龄而退出步兵预备队，我也会考虑做同样的事情。<br><br>最近的剧变中另一个令人不快的现实是，起源于欧洲的以色列犹太人（称为德系犹太人）和起源于伊斯兰世界的犹太人（米兹拉希姆，我们当地的简写）之间存在断层线。我们花费巨大努力假装我们的辩论只是关于政策，而不是身份，但事实并非如此。许多扎根于卡萨布兰卡和阿尔及尔等地、被该国东欧创始人和官方叙述边缘化的家庭所感受到的不满并没有消失——相反，它似乎还在增长。<br><br>参加示威活动的任何人都知道，抗议者大多是德系中产阶级。看守并偶尔粗暴对待我们的警察主要是工人阶级米兹拉希姆，传统的利库德集团的普通成员也是如此。战斗机中队、突击队和情报机构中的大多数人都是德系犹太人和自由派人士。学院和技术董事会非常相似。这一社会学事实对我们的社会没有任何好处。这里至少有一半的犹太人是米兹拉希人，但我们从未有过米兹拉希人总理，最高法院也严重缺乏种族多样性。<br><br>良好的领导力可以解决这一分歧。但对于内塔尼亚胡这样的政客来说，分歧不是问题，而是武器。他希望利用选民的愤怒作为政治飞机的燃料，赌这会推动他向上而不是把我们所有人炸得粉身碎骨。利库德集团与定居者和极端正统派的不满联盟现在公开嘲笑最高法院是敌对的德系精英，公务员部门是“深层国家”，空军飞行员是享有特权的小子，军官是叛徒。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-limit-supreme-court-power-protests/674819/">纳坦·萨克斯：以色列处于边缘</a><br><br>即使在反对者中，内塔尼亚胡也享有政治大师的声誉。这一声誉与许多其他关于 2023 年垃圾堆的假设一样。内塔尼亚胡是一个失去了一切的空壳，除了他的旧男中音。他释放的力量已经脱离了他的控制，现在其他人掌权了，这些人不把政治视为解决问题的机制，而是把政治视为掠夺、对抗和复仇的竞技场。<br><br>我在这里的这些年里从来没有听到过这么多关于移民的谈论。以色列人曾经认为我们的内部问题和外部冲突可以得到解决，所以坚持下去是有道理的。今天，情况恰恰相反。我们似乎并没有找到一个令人满意的解决方案。<br><br>当我 1995 年搬到以色列时，找到 Nike 或 Levis 很困难，旅行也成了一种奢侈。 2023 年，抗议者穿着你在柏林或帕洛阿尔托看到的同样的 Zara 背心和 Garmins 手表。以色列中产阶级说英语。他们看<i>《继承之战》</i> 。他们还有其他选择。如果这个政府不是反常而是新常态，许多人就会离开。<br><br>议会的长方形主体坐落在耶路撒冷一个整洁的区域，以色列博物馆对面，沿着最高法院的街道，周围是栅栏和花坛。我在日常事务中经常经过这里，它看起来总是井然有序且持久。但周一，同一条道路被封闭，警车和蓝白相间的旗帜纷乱。建筑物内部，瓦解的力量正在发挥作用。一切似乎都进展得很快，快得超出了我们的理解。国家大厦就像全息图一样脆弱，仿佛我的手可以穿过它们。中央隔离带上成排种植的粉红色花朵消失在抗议者的运动鞋下，然后消失在将我们推开的马蹄下。我又低头一看。灌溉管道已被拔掉，花坛一片泥泞。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-judicial-reform-and-protests-netanyahu/674849/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-judicial-reform-and-protests-netanyahu/674849/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[So Maybe Facebook Didn’t Ruin Politics]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> 2020 年大选期间在幕后进行的社交媒体大规模实验表明，美国民主没有简单的解决办法。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/6qaHl5fnf5Ou-fFoSLbcM4k3T3Y=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/FB_election_polarization_3b/original.jpg" alt="红色和蓝色“喜欢”图标的插图，通过箭头网络连接" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>插图由 Ben Kothe / 大西洋月刊</figcaption></figure><em>《科学》</em>杂志上的一个新特别<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.adj7023">包裹</a>的标题是“<span class="smallcaps">民主被拦截</span>”。 “平台推送是否在 2020 年美国总统大选期间播下了深刻分歧的种子？”大问题。 （可怕的问题！）根据今天发表在世界上最负盛名的两本研究期刊<em>《科学》</em>和<em>《自然》</em>上的一组研究，令人惊讶的答案是：“可能不会，或者在任何短期内都不会，但人们永远无法真正确定。”<br><br>毫无疑问，美国政治格局是两极分化的，而且在过去几十年里变得<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/05/us-democrat-republican-partisan-polarization/629925/">更加两极分化</a>。互联网在其中发挥了一定作用，这似乎既合乎逻辑又明显，今天阴谋论和不良信息比社交媒体之前更容易传播，距离我们还不到三年的时间，一场<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/10/facebook-papers-democracy-election-zuckerberg/620478/">部分由利用社交媒体策划的</a>叛乱发生了。 Facebook 创建的工具。轶事证据很能说明问题。但我们现在拥有的最好的科学传达了一些不同的信息。<br><br> <em>《科学》</em>杂志上的三篇新论文和<em>《自然》</em>杂志上的一篇新论文是 Facebook 和 Instagram 背后的公司 Meta 与学术科学家之间罕见、密切合作的首批成果。作为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://research.facebook.com/2020-election-research/">2020 年选举研究项目</a>的一部分，该项目由德克萨斯大学奥斯汀分校教授塔利亚·斯特劳德 (Talia Stroud) 和纽约大学教授约书亚·塔克 (Joshua Tucker) 领导，调查人员团队获得了大量访问 Facebook 和 Instagram 用户数据的权限，并允许进行需要直接操纵数万名同意用户的提要的实验。 Meta 没有补偿其学术合作伙伴，也没有对研究方法、分析或结论拥有最终决定权。不过，为了保护用户隐私，该公司确实对合作伙伴的数据访问设定了一定的限制。它还支付研究本身的费用，并在过去向一些学者（包括主要作者）提供研究经费。 Meta 员工是这些论文的合著者之一。<br><br>这种动态本质上是令人担忧的：Meta，一家非常强大的公司，长期以来一直因<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/12/facebook-doomsday-machine/617384/">破坏美国民主的缝隙</a>以及将外部研究人员<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/10/facebook-oversight-data-independent-research/620557/">拒之门外而受到</a>批评，现在它支持的研究表明，<em>嘿，也许社交媒体的影响是还不错</em>。与此同时，该项目为了解两个最大的社交平台上的实际行为提供了一个独特的窗口，并且似乎经过了合法的审查。威斯康星大学麦迪逊分校新闻学教授迈克尔·瓦格纳（Michael Wagner）担任此次合作的独立观察员，他的评价<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.adi2430">收录</a>在<em>《科学</em>》特刊中：“我的结论是，该团队进行了严格、仔细检查、透明、道德和路径-突破性的研究，”他写道，但他补充说，这种独立性只能通过公司分配来实现。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/10/facebook-oversight-data-independent-research/620557/">阅读：没有人可以看到 Facebook</a><br><br>新发表的研究单独来看很有趣，但放在一起阅读时才更有意义。首先，宾夕法尼亚大学传播学教授桑德拉·冈萨雷斯·拜隆 (Sandra González-Bailón) 领导的一项<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.ade7138">研究</a>证实了社交媒体上存在回音室。尽管<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://andyguess.com/publication/guess-2020-everything/">之前使用网络浏览数据的研究</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://academic.oup.com/qje/article-abstract/126/4/1799/1924154">发现</a>，大多数人总体上具有相当平衡的信息饮食，但似乎并非每个在线环境都是如此。 González-Bailón 的团队总结道：“Facebook 作为一个社交和信息环境，在意识形态上基本上是隔离的，而被事实核查人员评为“虚假”的新闻条目往往聚集在该网络的“同质保守角落”。因此，该平台的回音室可能是真实的，错误信息在政治光谱的一侧影响更大。但这会对用户的政治产生什么影响呢？<br><br>在另外三篇论文中，研究人员能够通过在激烈的选举季节实时进行的随机实验来研究信息环境在多大程度上加剧了分裂。他们还测试了一些关于如何修复社交媒体的著名理论（例如通过减少病毒式内容）是否会产生任何影响。由达特茅斯学院政府教授布伦丹·尼汉 (Brendan Nyhan) 领导的发表在<em>《自然》</em>杂志上的这项研究尝试了另一种方法：在他们的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06297-w">实验</a>中，尼汉和他的团队在三个月内大幅减少了人们在 Facebook 上看到的“志趣相投的来源”的内容量2020 年选举周期期间和之后。从 9 月下旬到 12 月，研究人员对大约 7,000 名同意用户的提要中的内容进行了“降级”，如果这些内容来自任何来源（朋友、群组或页面），预计会分享用户的政治信仰。干预没有起到作用。回音室确实变得不那么强烈，但根据后续调查的结果，受影响的用户的政治观点保持不变。与对照组相比，实验参与者的意识形态信仰最终变得极端，对民主党和共和党的态度也同样极端。<br><br>发表在<em>《科学》杂志</em>上的另外两项实验研究也得出了类似的结论。两项研究均由普林斯顿大学政治和公共事务助理教授安德鲁·盖斯 (Andrew Guess) 领导，并且都基于从 9 月下旬到 2020 年 12 月的三个月期间收集的数据。在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.add8424">一项实验</a>中，盖斯的团队试图删除所有被朋友、群组或大量 Facebook 用户提要的页面转发的帖子，以测试这样做是否可以减轻病毒式传播的有害影响。 （由于一些技术限制，仍然保留了少量转发的帖子。）干预成功地减少了人们对政治新闻的接触，并降低了他们对网站的整体参与度，但再一次，新闻推送的调整并没有减少人们对政治新闻的接触。用户的政治极化程度或改变他们的政治态度。<br><br> Guess 和同事的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.abp9364">第二个实验</a>同样直率：它选择性地关闭了某些 Facebook 和 Instagram 用户的动态排名算法，而是按时间顺序呈现帖子。这一变化导致用户在平台上花费的总体时间减少，并且与帖子的互动频率降低。尽管如此，就政治极化而言，按时间顺序排列的用户最终与控制者没有什么不同。关闭平台算法三个月并没有削弱他们的信念。<br><br>换句话说，平均而言，这三种干预措施都未能将用户从意识形态极端中拉回来。与此同时，它们还产生了许多其他影响。 “这些平台上的实验，可以说它们所展示的是已经提出的突出的、相对简单的修复方案——它们带来了意想不到的后果，”盖斯告诉我。其中一些是违反直觉的。盖斯以删除转发帖子的实验为例。这减少了人们从不可信来源看到的新闻帖子数量，也减少了他们从可信来源看到的新闻帖子数量。事实上，研究人员发现，受影响的用户对主流新闻媒体的曝光率下降了 62%，并且在有关近期新闻事件的测验中表现出较差的迹象。<br><br>所以这很新颖。但四项研究叙述的要点——网上回声室很重要，但可能不足以解释线下政治冲突——不应感到陌生。 “从我作为该领域研究人员的角度来看，令人惊讶的发现可能比一般公众要少，”未参与这项研究的密歇根大学副教授乔什·帕塞克告诉我。 “回音室故事是一种令人难以置信的媒体叙事，它具有认知意义，”但它不太可能解释人们实际信仰的大部分差异。这种立场曾经看起来比今天更加<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/health-and-science/2018/01/weve-been-told-were-living-in-a-post-truth-age-dont-believe-it.html">逆反</a>。 “我们的结果与政治学的许多研究结果一致，”盖斯说。 “你不会发现人们的信息环境对态度、观点或自我报告的政治参与等事物产生重大影响。”<br><br>算法很强大，但人也很强大。 Nyhan 团队进行的实验减少了用户提要中出现的志同道合的内容数量，但受试者仍然寻找他们同意的内容。事实上，与对照组相比，他们最终更有可能参与他们所看到的向唱诗班讲道的帖子。 “重要的是要记住，人们不仅仅是算法提供给他们的信息的被动接收者，”尼汉告诉我，他还在 2018 年与人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://kf-site-production.s3.amazonaws.com/media_elements/files/000/000/133/original/Topos_KF_White-Paper_Nyhan_V1.pdf">合着了一篇题为“避免回声室关于回声室”的文献评论</a>。他补充说，我们都会选择追随谁、追随什么。这些选择可能会受到平台推荐的影响，但它们仍然是<em>我们的</em>。<br><br>研究人员肯定会在这一点和其他方面受到一些阻力，特别是考虑到他们与 Facebook 的密切合作关系以及一系列可能被解读为让这家社交媒体巨头摆脱困境的调查结果。 （即使社交媒体回声室并没有像人们所怀疑的那样扭曲政治格局，Meta 仍然<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/10/facebook-failed-the-world/620479/">在努力</a>控制其平台上的错误信息。令人担忧的是，正如冈萨雷斯-拜隆的论文所指出的那样，新闻报道是最受关注的研究期间在 Facebook 上发布的次数题为“宾夕法尼亚州垃圾桶中发现的军事选票——大多数都是特朗普选票。”）Facebook 全球事务负责人尼克·克莱格 (Nick Clegg) 在今天发表的一篇关于这项研究的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://about.fb.com/news/2023/07/research-social-media-impact-elections/">博客文章</a>中表示，取得了胜利“越来越多的研究表明，几乎没有证据表明社交媒体会造成有害的‘情感’两极分化，或者对关键的政治态度、信仰或行为产生任何有意义的影响。”尽管研究人员承认这种令人不安的情况，但无法回避的事实是，如果 Meta 决定终止合作，他们的研究可能会陷入危险。<br><br>柏林马克斯·普朗克人类发展研究所的研究员菲利普·洛伦茨-斯普林（Philipp Lorenz-Spreen）没有参与这项研究，他承认这种设置并不“适合真正独立的研究”，但他告诉我，他“完全相信这是一项伟大的努力。我确信这些研究是我们目前在美国大选期间社交媒体上对美国人口的最好的研究。”<br><br>这很大，但综合考虑，也相当小。这些研究仅涵盖了美国近代政治史上一个非常特定时期的三个月。对于此类实验来说，三个月是一个重要的窗口期——洛伦茨-斯宾称之为“令人印象深刻的长”——但在历史力量的漩涡中，它似乎微不足道。如果社交媒体算法在 2020 年底的特定时间段内没有造成太大的选民两极分化，那么它们可能仍然会在 2016 年大选前以及之前的几年里加深美国政治中的裂痕在那之后。<br><br>德国康斯坦茨大学数据科学教授 David Garcia 也在<em>《自然》杂志</em>上发表了一篇<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://06%20https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-02325-x">文章</a>；他的结论是，这些实验虽然意义重大，但“并不排除新闻推送算法导致两极分化加剧的可能性。”这些实验是在个人身上进行的，正如加西亚在一封电子邮件中向我所说的那样，两极分化是“一种集体现象”。他说，“即使可能的话”，要完全证明算法在美国和其他国家的两极分化加剧中发挥的作用，将是一项更加艰巨的任务。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 18:03:06 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/meta-facebook-political-polarization-studies/674841/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/meta-facebook-political-polarization-studies/674841/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Song That First Captured Sinéad O’Connor’s Power]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在《Nothing Compares 2 U》让她家喻户晓之前，这位爱尔兰歌手第一张专辑中的一首单曲让她成为了一股创造力。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/lmLTodOiq2ye6mR1qmm64rNRRFk=/0x402:3735x2503/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_168935759/original.jpg" alt="歌手西妮德·奥康纳 (Sinéad O’Connor) 在音乐会上表演" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>弗兰斯·谢勒肯斯/雷德芬斯/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>凯瑟琳·弗格森 (Kathryn Ferguson) 于 2022 年拍摄的关于西妮德·奥康纳 (Sinéad O&#39;Connor) 生活和职业生涯的纪录片<em>《Nothing Compares》</em>中有一个坦率的时刻，这位歌手说：“成为一名流行歌星对我来说真是太震惊了。这不是我想要的。我只是想尖叫。” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/26/arts/music/sinead-oconnor-dead.html">昨天去世</a>，享年 56 岁的奥康纳在 80 年代末就成名了，当时她才十几岁。 1990 年，她翻唱的 Prince 的《Nothing Compares 2 U》不仅成为了她的标志性歌曲，而且还登上了许多国家的排行榜榜首——这一横扫将一个害羞的爱尔兰孩子推到了国际关注的烈日之下。<br><br>她不但没有控制自己的声音，反而继续尖叫。多年来，她的许多有争议的抗议和声明往往掩盖了她令人惊叹的作品。当人们发誓要谋杀你时（就像她在<em>《周六夜现场</em>》撕毁了教皇约翰·保罗二世的照片后所做的那样），而弗兰克·西纳特拉公开威胁要攻击你（就像当她拒绝在一个体育场播放美国国歌时，他所做的那样） 1990 年新泽西音乐会），很难将注意力转回到真正让你出名的事情上：你的音乐。<br><br>她成为一名流行歌星——不仅仅是任何流行歌星，而是有史以来最独特、最直言不讳、最有影响力的歌星之一——这一事实可能让她感到惊讶。但这对她的粉丝来说并不意外。没有什么比她的第一首热门歌曲“Mandinka”更能说明这一点了。这首歌成为英国前 20 名热门单曲，是她 1987 年出色的首张唱片《 <em>The Lion and the Cobra》</em>中最出色的单曲，也是显而易见的耳熟能详的单曲。这是一张雄心勃勃的专辑，收集了童年创伤的黑暗描述（“特洛伊”）以及对欲望和同意的分层探索（“我想要你（把手放在我身上）”）。在这些更深沉、要求更高的单曲中，<em>狮子和眼镜蛇</em>需要一个乐观的邀请。就是“曼丁卡”。 <br><br><div class="oembed" data-oembed-name="www.youtube.com" data-oembed-src="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h08pCvyKfbs"><figure class="c-embedded-video"><div class="embed-wrapper" style="display: block; position:relative; width:100%; height:0; overflow:hidden; padding-bottom:75.00%;"><iframe allow="autoplay; fullscreen; encrypted-media; picture-in-picture;" allowfullscreen="true" class="embedly-embed lazyload" data-src="//cdn.embedly.com/widgets/media.html?src=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fembed%2Fh08pCvyKfbs%3Ffeature%3Doembed&amp;display_name=YouTube&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3Dh08pCvyKfbs&amp;image=https%3A%2F%2Fi.ytimg.com%2Fvi%2Fh08pCvyKfbs%2Fhqdefault.jpg&amp;key=8164a61223cb4585ad276041728caca9&amp;type=text%2Fhtml&amp;schema=youtube" frameborder="0" height="480" scrolling="no" style="position:absolute; width:100%; height:100%; top:0; left:0; border:0;" title="YouTube 嵌入" width="640" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></figure></div> 《Mandinka》是奥康纳十几岁的时候写的，当时她正在伦敦努力成为一名有抱负的外籍人士，这首歌曲是一首推动性的赞歌，跨越了流行音乐和松散的另类摇滚流派，直到它在商业上取得了全面的胜利。 90 年代。歌词本身并没有传达叙事，但就像奥康纳的许多歌曲一样，《Mandinka》综合并投射了一系列图像、指责和咒语。她的话语中凝聚着对父权制的一系列不满，因为父权制拒绝为了目的而牺牲诗歌。标题来自亚历克斯·哈利（Alex Haley）的<em>《根源》</em> （Roots），其中提到了冈比亚曼丁卡族（Mandinka）。 《Mandinka》稍微领先于它的时代，但它也与同时代的歌曲（如 Neneh Cherry 的《Buffalo Stance》和 Enya 的《Orinoco Flow》）处于同一阵营。 （毫不奇怪，她的爱尔兰艺术家同胞恩雅客串了<em>《狮子与眼镜蛇》</em> 。）<br><br> 《Mandinka》的核心是一首反抗之歌。奥康纳将她能做到的每一点细节和音域——咆哮、吟诵、咕咕声，还有，是的，尖叫——都投入到了这首歌中，结果是对传统的一击。伤害是“曼丁卡”DNA 的一部分，尽管奥康纳对自己抵御伤害的能力感到欣喜若狂：“我不知道羞耻/我感觉不到痛苦/我看不到火焰，”她唱道毒液。再次，反抗。但这并不是否认或虚张声势，而是承认她如何自豪地使用自己的疤痕组织作为原材料。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/04/how-nothing-compares-2-u-endured/391122/">阅读：“Nothing Compares 2 U”如何经受住考验</a><br><br>“很快我就能把我的心交给你，”奥康纳在《Mandinka》的结尾高呼道。她正是这样做的：三年后，华丽浪漫的“Nothing Compares 2 U”问世，成为大多数人听到奥康纳名字时立即想到的歌曲。但《Nothing Compares 2 U》的力量部分源于这样一个事实：奥康纳已经证明自己有能力在<em>《狮子和眼镜蛇》</em>中发挥更大的力量，尤其是在《曼丁卡》中。她第一次出现在美国电视节目是<em>《大卫深夜秀》</em> ，她在这首单曲中的表演很能说明问题。她穿着一件像朋克摇滚盔甲一样的尖刺牛仔夹克，双臂放在身前，前后扭动，就像她在拳击场上躲避打击一样。<br><br>也许对《Mandinka》影响最简洁的致敬是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rB3qDlu5Nvg">Fiona Apple 于 2017 年发布在 YouTube 上的一段视频</a>。在视频中，Apple 躺在床上，拿着笔记本电脑，一边跟着奥康纳 1989 年格莱美表演一边唱歌一边打拳。这是一个历史性的事件：当年获得最佳摇滚女歌手提名的奥康纳臭名昭著地将公敌的靶心标志画在头上，以抗议格莱美新颁发的最佳说唱表演奖是在镜头外授予的。 （昨天在 Twitter 上，该组织的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/MrChuckD/status/1684278409868763160">Chuck D</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/FlavorFlav/status/1684305143574003715">Flavor Flav</a>都记得这次抗议。）<br><br>当副歌响起时，苹果提高音量并亲吻屏幕。这是一种快乐的释放和赋权的姿态，反映了歌曲本身。 “我并不是故意要坚强，”奥康纳在弗格森的纪录片开头说道。 “我并没有对自己说，<em>我必须坚强</em>。我不知道我很坚强。”然而，只要听一听“曼丁卡”，其他人就能知道、感受到并发现自己被她的力量所增强。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 18:02:19 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/sinead-oconnor-legacy-mandinka-song/674844/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/sinead-oconnor-legacy-mandinka-song/674844/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[How Jason Aldean Explains Donald Trump (And Vice Versa)]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>与前总统一样，阿尔丁利用了共和党基础选民的焦虑情绪。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/GXlp-ZhPBPf1aqJJLScHfLGBjT4=/89x0:1611x856/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/Screenshot_2023_07_26_at_11.56.19_AM/original.png" alt="杰森·阿尔丁 (Jason Aldean) 音乐视频中的剧照" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>杰森·阿尔丁/YouTube</figcaption></figure>乡村音乐明星杰森·阿尔丁对小镇私刑主义的颂歌所取得的商业成功有助于解释唐纳德·特朗普对红色美国的持续控制。<br><br>阿尔丁的好斗新歌《在小镇尝试》以音乐方式重复了特朗普自从政以来所表达的核心信息：保守派认为美国正遭受来自多元文化、城市化现代社会的非同寻常的攻击。留下任何必要的手段来消除威胁都是合理的。<br><br>在阿尔丁的歌词和他为歌曲制作的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b1_RKu-ESCY">视频</a>中，这些非凡的手段围绕着治安维持力量的威胁，以坚守阵线，打击他所描述的大城市的犯罪和混乱。在特朗普的政治信息中，这些手段是他为了“让美国再次伟大”而系统性地破坏国家规范和潜在的法律。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/06/trumps-rhetoric-of-white-nostalgia/485192/">阅读：特朗普关于白人怀旧的言论</a><br><br>与特朗普一样，阿尔丁也利用了共和党基础选民普遍存在的焦虑情绪，即他们的价值观在文化和种族多样性不断增加的不断变化的美国中被边缘化。每个人都传达出这样的信息：需要采取极端措施，甚至延伸到暴力，才能防止这种流离失所。<br><br> “即使对于家乡的主流保守派选民来说……我们必须进行文化反革命的想法已经根深蒂固，”保守派道德与公共政策中心的研究员帕特里克·布朗告诉我。 “乡村音乐是实现这一目标的一个渠道这一事实一点也不令人惊讶。”<br><br>阿尔丁的好战歌谣<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.american1.com/aldeans-anthem-stirs-controversy-singer-stands-firm/?fbclid=IwAR1dJFKfDIccobxruZSvRQ-__dL3B0EB9FX3wa2g_k4gAww6LhTU8KlROdY_aem_AaykaK9c4E033DtERVYBeawFQjIYpdx_m03qA0kVTummaZB4hShbSnkaKyA3RB09stk&amp;mibextid=2JQ9oc">在受到批评者谴责后，下载量增加了十倍以上</a>，它遵循了乡村歌曲反对对美国现状的挑战的传统。这种抵制在李·格林伍德 (Lee Greenwood) 的早期里程碑作品《上帝保佑美国》(God Bless the USA) 中得到了体现，该书自 1984 年发行以来一直是共和党集会的主要内容。阿尔丁甚至更直接地引用了梅尔·哈格德 (Merle Haggard) 1970 年的乡村大片，该片警告那些反对越南战争和“破坏我的国家”的人，正如标题所宣称的那样，将会看到“我战斗的一面”。 （此前，哈格德在他 1969 年的热门歌曲《 <i>Okie From Muskogee》</i>中表达了类似的想法，该歌曲颂扬了美国小镇，“我们不会在大街上烧掉我们的选秀卡。”）<br><br>在理查德·尼克松担任总统期间，哈加德的歌曲（他后来的矛盾心理）成为保守派的颂歌，就像罗纳德·里根执政期间格林伍德的歌曲一样。这个时机并非巧合：在这两个时期，这些领导人都将共和党定义为反对扰乱国家的社会变革。这又是一个这样的时刻：特朗普将自己的吸引力集中在将自己描绘成他的支持者与一系列影子势力之间的最后一道防线——包括“全球主义精英”、“深层政府”、暴力的城市少数群体和无证移民——据称威胁他们。<br><br>阿尔丁虽然是特朗普的坚定支持者，但他是一名表演者，而不是政治家；他的歌表达的是一种态度，而不是一个节目。然而，阿尔丁和特朗普都利用了保守派白人基督徒中普遍存在的信念，尤其是阿尔丁神话般的小镇上的基督徒，他们认为，在一个不可阻挡地变得更加多元化、世俗化和城市化的社会中，他们是偏见的真正受害者。<br><br>自2016年特朗普首次当选以来的多项全国民意调查中，十分之九的共和党人表示美国的基督教受到攻击；多达四分之三的人同意，对白人的偏见现在与对少数族裔的歧视一样严重；大约十分之七的人同意，社会只是因为表现得像男人而惩罚男人，而且白人现在是美国社会最受歧视的群体。<br><br>相信特朗普也有这些担忧，并致力于解决这些问题，这一信念始终是他与共和党选民联系的关键。每当他做了或说了一些看似站不住脚的事情时，共和党选民就会聚集在他周围——即使在 1 月 6 日的叛乱中，这一过程现在似乎仍在重复。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://brightlinewatch.org/uncharted-territory-the-aftermath-of-presidential-indictments/">在由研究美国民主威胁的政治学家合作组织 Bright Line Watch 昨天发布的一项全国调查中</a>，60% 的共和党人（相比之下只有三分之一的独立人士和六分之一的民主党人）将 1 月 6 日的骚乱描述为合法的政治事件反对。只有略高于十分之一的共和党人表示，特朗普在 1 月 6 日或在其推翻 2020 年总统选举结果的更广泛竞选活动中的行为犯了罪行。<br><br> 1 月 6 日保守派中的修正主义粉饰有助于解释为什么阿尔丁在没有任何明显的矛盾或讽刺感的情况下，可以将他的歌曲集中在“好男孩，正确举起”的暴力幻想上，对那些“咒骂警察”的人进行惩罚”或“践踏国旗”。特朗普的支持者，其中许多人可能符合阿尔丁对“好男孩”的描述，他们在 2021 年袭击国会大厦时正是做了这些事情。（例​​如，1 月 6 日来自阿肯色州的骚乱者，本周被判处 52 个月监禁）因用旗帜袭击警察<i>而</i>被监禁。）然而，阿尔丁将这些歌词与不是叛乱的图像，而是在城市街道上横冲直撞的阴暗抗议者的图像结合在一起。<br><br>阿尔丁无视 1 月 6 日的袭击事件，同时强调 2020 年乔治·弗洛伊德被谋杀后有时与大规模种族正义抗议活动一起爆发的左翼暴力，阿尔丁和特朗普一样，明确声明了他认为这项法律的目的是针对谁。保护和压制的对象。该视频在视觉上强调了这一信息，因为它是在田纳西州法院外拍摄的，一名年轻的黑人于 1927 年在那里被私刑处死。阿尔丁表示，他不知道其中的联系，并且否认这首歌中有任何种族主义意图。但正如范德比尔特大学历史学家妮可·海默 (Nicole Hemmer) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/20/opinions/opinion-jason-aldean-video-cmt-vigilantism-hemmer/index.html">上周为 CNN.com 所写的那样</a>，“无论他承认与否，阿尔丁的歌曲和一名少年被谋杀的法院都提醒人们，从历史上看，诉诸所谓的法律和秩序往往既依赖于正式的法律程序，也依赖于白人的自卫行为。”<br><br>最重要的是，阿尔丁的歌曲捕捉到了右翼被围困的感觉。它在流行文化中反映出共和党基础中同样的好斗情绪，自特朗普 2020 年失败以来，这种好斗情绪鼓励全国各地的共和党领导人在几乎所有方面对民主党和自由派利益采取更激进的策略。<br><br>例如，田纳西州的共和党立法多数派<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/04/tennessee-expulsions-republican-gop/673709/">驱逐了两名年轻的黑人民主党州代表</a>，蒙大拿州的共和党多数派谴责了一名跨性别民主党州代表，并禁止她参加会议。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2021/12/republican-states-rights-restrictions/621101/">共和党控制的州正在推进</a>煽动性政策，这些政策在几年前可能被认为是不可想象的， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/texass-immigration-policy-biden/674784/">比如德克萨斯州政府通过在边境安装刀片刺网和在格兰德河漂浮浮标来阻止移民的计划</a>。众议院议长凯文·麦卡锡提出弹劾乔·拜登的可能性。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/bud-light-boycott-consumer-effect/674446/">百威淡啤仅仅因为与跨性别影响者合作</a>开展促销项目而遭到抵制，这代表了右翼广泛反革命的另一个战线。特朗普在竞选中承诺进一步升级：他表示，如果连任，他将以前所未有的方式动员联邦权力，对保守派针对蓝色目标进行所谓的“报复”，例如，派遣国民警卫队进入民主党——管理城市打击犯罪，推行大规模的无证移民驱逐计划，并公开部署司法部来对付他的政治对手。<br><br>道德与公共政策中心的布朗指出，尽管州和国家层面的共和党人都在推动这一令人毛骨悚然的议程，但他们认为自己并不是在发动一场文化战争，而是在回应媒体自由派针对他们发起的一场文化战争。 、学术界、大公司和倡导团体。他说，共和党人的主流观点是“我们正试图在这里采取防御行动。我们没有侵略；我们正在受到侵略。”<br><br>在不断发展的美国，对被流离失所的恐惧已经成为激励共和党选民的最强大力量<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2012/11/the-coalition-of-transformation-vs-the-coalition-of-restoration/265512/">——我称之为</a>“复辟联盟”。从政治生涯一开始，特朗普就瞄准了这种感觉<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/06/trumps-rhetoric-of-white-nostalgia/485192/">，承诺“让美国<i>再次伟大”。</i>阿尔丁</a>同样回顾了他对美国未来的愿景， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://people.com/jason-aldean-stands-by-controversial-song-during-ohio-tour-stop-7564414">在一场音乐会上为他的歌曲辩护，表达了</a>他希望看到美国“在所有这些废话开始发生在我们身上之前，恢复到原来的样子”。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/03/working-class-white-voters-gop-house-agenda/673500/">阅读：工人阶级白人选民如何成为共和党的基础</a><br><br>正如布朗指出的那样，2024 年共和党总统竞选已经成为一场谁最致力于与左翼斗争、挖掘失去的美国的竞争。阿尔丁的歌曲和视频有助于解释原因。他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2022/06/red-and-blue-state-divide-is-growing-michael-podhorzer-newsletter/661377/">为该国红蓝阵营之间日益加深的冷战</a>写了一首战斗进行曲。在他的讲述中，就像特朗普一样，传统上保守的美国白人正受到社会力量的威胁，这些力量将抹去他们的生活方式。对于蓝色美国来说，阿尔丁描述的进程代表着一场早该进行的重新谈判，因为少数族裔和 LGBTQ 群体等先前被边缘化的群体需要更多的影响力和包容性。在《红色美国》中，他描述了一种需要无条件抵抗的生存威胁。<br><br>民意调查显示，尽管针对特朗普的可信刑事指控不断增加，但大多数共和党人正在通过在 2024 年提名竞选中再次团结起来支持特朗普来应对这一威胁。但《在小镇尝试一下》的真正信息是，无论特朗普个人发生什么，共和党联盟中的大多数选民几乎肯定会继续要求领导人，就像阿尔丁所说的“从小培养的好男孩”一样，他们渴望着与他们认为危及世界的一切事物作斗争。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 16:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/jason-aldean-donald-trump/674842/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/jason-aldean-donald-trump/674842/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[American Family Life Should Not Be This Volatile]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>欢迎来到颤抖的时代。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/svoxez6gbJG4KFeL--3BSnqxm9s=/0x0:3333x4166/648x810/media/img/2023/07/27/MG179418_copy/original.jpg" alt="一个男人俯身在他的孩子身上的剪影" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Gueorgui Pinkhassov / Magnum</figcaption></figure><span class="smallcaps">为人父母总是充满不可预测性</span>：凌晨两点醒来、学校打来电话、那些让<em>我胃痛的</em>可怕话语。这种日常差异通常源于生病或受惊的孩子，并且是家庭生活基本动态的一部分。然而，今天的美国父母也面临着日益严重的外部干扰和旨在提供稳定的机构的退化。其结果是，许多家庭经常会因为一些问题而陷入困境，这些问题不仅仅是不方便，但还不是灾难性的。这会滋生父母的压力、不安全感和疲惫。简而言之，美国人已经进入了一个颤抖的时代。<br><br>过去半个世纪以来，这个国家一直在走这条道路。从 20 世纪 70 年代开始，一系列经济和社会政策决策导致了政治学家雅各布·哈克 (Jacob Hacker) 所说的从政府和企业到家庭的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-great-risk-shift-the-new-economic-insecurity-and-the-decline-of-the-american-dream-jacob-s-hacker/9780190844141?affiliate_id=atl-347">巨大风险转移</a>”。哈克的想法主要指的是经济变化，例如私营部门从有保障的养老金转向依赖股票市场的401(k)s。但威斯康星大学麦迪逊分校的社会学家杰西卡·卡拉科告诉我，这种“DIY社会”的概念可以延伸到父母——尤其是母亲——被要求“把一切整合在一起”的多种方式。例如，双职工家庭的崛起并没有得到负担得起的儿童保育或强制带薪休假等政策的满足。相反，家庭被迫在混乱且竞争激烈的市场中穿行，以获得日托和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/01/summer-day-camps-activities-childcare/672837/">夏令营</a>等基本服务，而且他们在很大程度上依靠自己来应对任何故障。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/06/us-paid-parental-leave-child-welfare-tax-credit/661276/">阅读：美国让父母独自一人是有原因的</a><br><br>2020 年代的新情况是这些故障发生得更加频繁。考虑一下家庭近年来面临的一系列挑战。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/17/health/formula-shortage-one-year-later/index.html">婴儿配方奶粉</a>以及<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/01/05/why-childrens-tylenol-shortage">泰诺</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aap.org/en/pages/amoxicillin-shortage-antibiotic-options-for-common-pediatric-conditions/">阿莫西林</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/students-struggle-academically-fight-in-schools-amid-adderall-shortage-209d01e0">阿得拉</a>等儿童药物严重短缺。儿童保育变得<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/07/us-childcare-programs-expensive-underfunded/670927/">更加稀缺和昂贵</a>——而且，由于人员短缺，项目经常<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://vtdigger.org/2022/08/02/closure-of-a-child-care-center-in-essex-junction-sends-families-scrambling-for-options/">在没有通知的情况下</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.kcrg.com/2023/07/25/families-hunt-new-child-care-after-iowa-city-facility-suddenly-closes/">关闭</a>或减少时间。酷热<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/01/us/michgan-schools-heat.html">迫使学校停课</a>；来自加拿大的野火烟雾导致美国一些<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2023/07/23/summer-camp-canada-wildfire-smoke/">夏令营</a>推迟了开始时间。<br><br>这种波动的部分原因是气候变化、公共政策决策或企业利润最大化。其中一些是多种因素共同作用的结果。婴儿配方奶粉危机主要<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/doj-investigating-abbott-plant-at-the-center-of-2022-baby-formula-shortage#:~:text=The%20factory's%20closure%20in%20February,banks%2C%20friends%20and%20doctor's%20offices.">是由一家工厂关闭造成的，</a>政策制定者让少数公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pbs.org/newshour/economy/the-current-baby-formula-shortage-sheds-light-on-longstanding-weaknesses-within-the-industry">几乎控制了整个市场，</a>这预示着这一困境。此外，正如劳工经济学家亚伦·索杰纳 (Aaron Sojourner) 告诉我的那样，“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.demos.org/sites/default/files/publications/Scheduling_Hourly_Workers_Demos.pdf">即时调度</a>”模式已显着增加，这种模式下，企业以最少的员工进行运营，这些员工可以在很短的时间内被召回或送回家。 ——低工资行业，包括零售、食品服务和呼叫中心。这会导致工人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.rsfjournal.org/content/8/5/24.abstract">（尤其是父母）</a>的生活不稳定，并且如果唯一的员工辞职或无法轮班，也会增加客户出现问题的风险。然而， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hrdive.com/news/a-running-list-of-states-and-localities-with-predictive-scheduling-mandates/540835/">只有一个州和少数城市</a>制定了限制即时调度的法律。<br><br>与此同时，数十年的忽视正在导致公共系统崩溃。缺乏足够的资金和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/recoding-america-why-government-is-failing-in-the-digital-age-and-how-we-can-do-better-jennifer-pahlka/9781250266774?affiliate_id=atl-347">现代化的流程</a>导致<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.baltimorebrew.com/2023/07/18/three-public-pools-have-yet-to-open-in-baltimore-hanging-residents-out-to-dry/">公共服务衰退</a>，政府办公室空心化，反应能力差。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.kcur.org/politics-elections-and-government/2023-05-10/missouri-families-cant-get-help-affording-child-care-because-of-bureaucratic-hurdles">完成儿童保育援助申请可能是一场噩梦</a>，即使是纽约和伊利诺伊州等资源充足的州最近也面临着<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://wgntv.com/news/illinois/some-childcare-providers-forced-to-close-after-not-getting-paychecks-from-state/">向儿童保育提供者及时付款</a>的重大问题。残疾儿童的家长<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnet.com/personal-finance/social-security-disability-claims-wait-record-high-how-to-avoid-delays/">面临着</a>创纪录的申请处理时间和极其有限的支持人员。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">震颤的时代有助于解释</span>人们对个人生活的看法与对国家发展方式的看法之间看似奇怪的脱节。 <em>《大西洋月刊》</em>的德里克·汤普森<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2022/06/american-economy-negative-perception-inflation/661149/">将这种现象描述</a>为“一切都很糟糕，但我很好”，指出健康的可支配收入等当代指标与经济低迷感之间的紧张关系。对于很多家长来说，我可能会将描述延伸到“一切都很糟糕；一切都很糟糕；”我在坚持，但接下来会出现什么问题呢？”<br><br>心理学家清楚， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://psychcentral.com/stress/stress-and-the-concept-of-control">合理的控制感</a>是心理健康的关键组成部分。必须担心加拿大的风向或在六家商店寻找药物来给孩子退烧，这不仅是实际的痛点，而且也是一个难题。它们营造了一种不稳定的总体气氛。一些幼儿家长<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/17/health/formula-shortage-one-year-later/index.html">表示，在货架再次被填满后，他们对配方奶粉供应仍心存恐惧和焦虑</a>。<br><br>无论一个人的银行账户有多少，这种持续的不稳定都会造成情感上的损失。研究表明，自大流行之前以来， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapediatrics/fullarticle/2789946">父母的心理健康状况显着下降</a>，近年来，父母的疲惫感、倦怠感和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsroom.thecignagroup.com/loneliness-epidemic-persists-post-pandemic-look">孤独感</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/05/well/family/parental-burnout-symptoms.html">都很高</a>。大约四分之三的父母非常或有些担心<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.capita.org/thinkofthechildren">气候变化会伤害他们的孩子</a>或他们认识的其他幼儿。这种压力和不安全感很容易<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.amazon.com/Tumbleweed-Society-Working-Caring-Insecurity/dp/0199957711?asin=0199957711&amp;revisionId=&amp;format=4&amp;depth=1">蔓延</a>到整个家庭。<br><br>一个简单的反驳是，这些都不是新鲜事。一个世纪前，父母不能指望抗生素，因为它们无法在市场上买到。但想想最近的过去：今天的父母比 20 世纪最后 25 年的父母更缺乏可预测性。正如斯坦福大学社会学家玛丽安·库珀 (Marianne Cooper) 在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/cut-adrift-families-in-insecure-times-marianne-cooper/9780520277670?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《漂流：不安全时代的家庭》一书中</em></a>所写的那样，风险大转移时开始的趋势在 2000 年代带来了收入的大幅增加和工作的不稳定。<br><br>此外，直到过去几十年，社会机构和债券已经做好了更好的准备来弥补这一差距。工会、兄弟会，尤其是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/28/opinion/religion-affiliation-community.html">信仰团体</a>不仅提供联系感，还提供物质支持，例如产后膳食或可以在紧要关头照顾孩子的值得信赖的人。这些网络的成员数量一直在稳步下降。<br><br>然而，永久的颤抖并不是不可避免的。政策制定者既可以稳定地面，又可以帮助家庭应对地震。第一步是将健康、可预测的家庭生活作为政策优先事项。加强儿童保育体系、提供强有力的带薪休假、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fortune.com/2023/04/17/irs-phone-wait-times-taxes/">对公共服务进行再投资</a>并降低<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2021/07/how-government-learned-waste-your-time-tax/619568/">其行政负担</a>以及限制及时调度的法律，都是将风险从家庭转移回政府和企业的方法。作为一项指导原则，政策制定者应减少混乱，解放父母和儿童，加深他们彼此之间以及社区的联系。<br><br>也许现状最可悲的是，这本应该是一个家庭充满奇迹的时代。我们生活在一个现代医学已经消除了许多儿童疾病并定期开发新<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/fda-approves-rsv-injection-infants-rcna94698">疗法</a>的时代。人们重新燃起对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/07/raising-kid-american-city/661506/">发展儿童友好型社区</a>的兴趣，这些社区可以通过 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tpl.org/parks-address-climate-change-report">扩大和升级公园</a>以及<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/2023/06/30/future-of-the-playground/">创建更多的天然游乐场</a>来抵御气候破坏。技术工具使与该国偏远地区的亲人联系比以往任何时候都更加容易。父母们可以有很多享受和期待——如果他们不是不断地为下一次摇晃做好准备的话。<br><br><small><em>​​当您使用此页面上的链接购买书籍时，我们会收到佣金。感谢您对大西洋月刊的支持</em><em>。</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 14:15:02 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/parenting-challenges-american-families-child-care/674839/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/parenting-challenges-american-families-child-care/674839/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Are You Plagued by the Feeling That Everyone Used to Be Nicer?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>不要屈服。这是一种心理错觉。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/GW_aY81Q6JVAd2ooOzHsyY0N5EM=/0x0:4796x2698/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/radio_atlantic_2/original.jpg" alt="照片中，两名年轻女子和一名年轻男子一起提着垃圾桶走在附近的人行道上。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>伦·特里夫诺/赫尔顿档案馆/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>我和我的兄弟争论了很久。他坚称，他现在在纽约长大的孩子们比我们小时候在同一社区长大的孩子安全得多。我碰巧知道这是荒谬的，多年来我一直试图说服他。我给他看了新闻报道、犯罪统计数据。有一次我什至下载了一份联邦调查局的报告，毫无疑问地显示 30 年前的纽约要危险得多。但他不为所动。他记得我们的童年更加温和、安全。我必须承认，有时候，当我在老邻居周围散步时，我会看到邮递员向 10 岁的我脱帽致意，而当我回家吃晚饭时，邻居们微笑着。<br><br>为什么我们很多人都有这样的感觉：年轻时，人们更友善、更有道德，并且更好地互相照顾？一位名叫亚当·马斯楚安尼 (Adam Mastroianni) 的实验心理学家也对这种持久的信念感到好奇，并最近在 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06137-x"><em>《自然》杂志</em></a>上发表了对这一现象的系统研究。<br><br>马斯楚安尼记录道，这种模糊的记忆是许多不同人群所共有的，并且感受相当强烈。他解释了这种幻觉是如何运作的，以及为什么它对我们有如此大的影响力。最重要的是，他解释了它如何不仅扭曲我们的个人关系，而且扭曲我们的文化和政治。在<em>大西洋广播电台</em>的这一集中，我与马斯楚安尼和特约撰稿人朱莉·贝克谈论了道德衰退的幻觉，以及为什么它如此强烈地持续存在。<br><br><em>每当</em><em>政治家或有抱负的政治家声称，“事情曾经更好，让我负责，我会让它们再次变得更好”时，这是我们听过很多次的非常古老的事情。它引起了我们的共鸣，也许是因为我们准备相信它，即使它不是真的。</em><br><br>请听这里的对话： <br><br><iframe class="lazyload" data-src="https://player.megaphone.fm/ATL9319336197" frameborder="no" height="200" scrolling="no" title="嵌入互动内容" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><em>在此订阅：</em> <a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/radio-atlantic/id1258635512"><em>Apple 播客</em></a><em>|</em> <a href="https://open.spotify.com/playlist/4PgNKjRJJWlaV6zuNr69BO"><em>Spotify</em></a> <em>|</em><a href="https://www.stitcher.com/show/radio-atlantic"><em>缝合器</em></a><em>|</em> <a href="https://podcasts.google.com/feed/aHR0cHM6Ly9mZWVkcy5tZWdhcGhvbmUuZm0vcmFkaW9hdGxhbnRpYw"><em>谷歌播客</em></a><em>|</em> <a href="https://pca.st/ccxU"><em>Pocket Casts</em></a><strong><em>为了清晰起见，以下剧集记录已被轻微编辑：</em></strong><br><br><strong>汉娜·罗辛：</strong>所以，朱莉，你知道的——尽管当其他人说人们过去比较友善时我会很生气，但我想我也可能有这种感觉。<br><br>如果我有童年的幻象，当我从操场走在街上时，我想象所有的邻居都会说：“嗨，小汉娜。” [<em>笑声</em>] 邮差过来了，你知道，他向我脱帽致意，还有老人在遛狗。<br><br>而且，你知道，我不知道这个记忆是否准确，但我确实有这样的感觉：人们更加友善。<br><br><strong>朱莉·贝克：</strong>你是在<em>罗杰斯先生的街区</em>长大的吗？或者那是什么？<br><br><strong>松香：</strong>没有；我实际上是在纽约皇后区长大的。所以这可能是、当然不是真的。 [<em>笑声。</em> ]<br><br>这是<em>大西洋广播电台</em>。我是汉娜·罗辛。 I invited my colleague Julie Beck on to talk about something that&#39;s always really bothered me. It&#39;s when people talk about how things are so much worse today than they were in the past.<br><br> And they say things like “Neighbors used to be nicer, and everyone used to smile at you and help you out.” And sometimes it&#39;s just grandpa chatter and you can pretty much ignore it. And then other times it turns into this “back when men were men and women were women”–type thing, which is more annoying.<br><br> <strong><em>Beck:</em></strong> <em>There&#39;s a benign wish to, like, tip your hat to the mailman. And then there&#39;s a “Oh, we need to bring back the social order of the 1950s.” And then you&#39;re like, “Whoa, how did we end up here?”</em><br><br> Julie analyzes psychological research and social trends, and she&#39;s also the host of another Atlantic podcast, <em>How to Talk to People</em> .<br><br> And she&#39;s here to help me understand this very interesting research that just emerged about this strong conviction people have that everything has gotten worse.<br><br> <strong><em>Adam Mastroianni</em></strong> <strong>:</strong> <em>So my whole life, I&#39;ve heard people say things like, “You used to be able to keep your doors unlocked at night,” or “You can&#39;t trust someone&#39;s word anymore.”</em><br><br> <em>And I always chafed at those kinds of statements. So part of it was wanting to prove everybody wrong. But part of it, too, was like,</em> Well, if they&#39;re right, this is a big problem. <em>And that&#39;s kind of where we got started.</em><br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> That is Adam Mastroianni. He recently published a paper in <em>Nature</em> called “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.experimental-history.com/p/the-illusion-of-moral-decline">The Illusion of Moral Decline</a> .” Adam is a psychologist, and he&#39;s the author of the science blog <em>Experimental History.</em> And he spent a decade systematically studying why we feel things were better in the past … and what it means.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> I think my first year of graduate school was when Trump got elected. And so obviously it was a moment of “Make America Great Again” being sort of the vibe of the day.<br><br> Seeing claims that “The past was good, the present is bad, put me in charge and I can bring the good past back” also just made me see how this is much more than, you know, uncles and brothers-in-law and people on the internet saying these things— that these claims resonate with people, and they help put people in the Oval Office.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yeah. I mean, I have to say, that&#39;s my motivation for being interested in your research, because I have always had a kind of detached curiosity about why this line resonates so strongly.<br><br> Like, why is it that—and it&#39;s not just American leaders, it&#39;s leaders all over the world—they can just say, “Oh, things were better back then,” and it immediately clicks for people? Like, they don&#39;t even have to explain it. You can just say, “You know, make America great again.” It&#39;s like four words, and all the assumptions are immediately there for people.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah. When I give talks in an academic context about this paper, what I start with is the end of Trump&#39;s inaugural speech, where he says, “You know, we&#39;ll make America wealthy again and proud again and safe again and great again.” And I point out that the most important word in those sentences isn&#39;t <em>America</em> or <em>safe</em> or <em>proud</em> or <em>strong</em> or <em>great</em> . It&#39;s <em>again</em> .<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yes!<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Just that word does a ton of work. Which is that: Well, if things used to be great but aren&#39;t now, it means something changed. It implies that we can change it back. It evokes a sense of loss, but also a sense of possibility of restoring the loss.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yeah. And it is the word <em>again</em> . It&#39;s like that one little word sort of resolves something emotionally for people. It&#39;s hard to understand exactly how it works, but you say the word <em>again</em> , and everyone&#39;s like, “Ah, you just filled a hole for me.”你知道？ What exactly do you mean when you say “moral decline,” and why, if it&#39;s an illusion, does it feel so real?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> There are a few totally reasonable hypotheses about what people might think of when they talk about moral decline. It might be that everyone means, like, “I heard that the 1950s were a really good time. And so what I&#39;m really telling you is things have declined since then.” Not that they got worse in the past 10 years; that they got worse, you know, 20 years ago or 50 years ago. And we&#39;re just living in the bad times now.<br><br> In a later study, we asked people go back even further than that. “What about 20 years before that? What about 40 years before that?” And what they told us there is—“Before I arrived, nothing was happening. Things were good. Then I got born, and then things started to go downhill.”<br><br> And what&#39;s especially interesting is: It doesn&#39;t matter when you were born. So the people who were 30 told us it happened 30 years ago. The people who were 60 told us it happened 60 years ago.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Wait, really? So literally, people think the decline began when they came on this earth?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah. So, I mean, we don&#39;t ask, like, the day before or the day after. But the question that we asked was: “Rate how kind, honest, nice, and good people are today. What about the year in which you were 20?” And people told us it was better then.<br><br> “What about the year in which you were born?” And people told us it was even better then. And then we asked, “What about 20 years before that? And 40 years before that?”<br><br> And there&#39;s no difference in people&#39;s answers. That line is flat. It&#39;s only when we asked about “20 years after your birth” that the line goes down.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> That is so interesting. I don&#39;t think I fully grasped that. So people are projecting whatever personal difficulties or struggles of life—now maybe I&#39;m extrapolating—onto the whole of humanity, like they&#39;re protecting their own life span onto a historical, broader cultural, political life span.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah. And I mean, this is a bias of people&#39;s memory, because you don&#39;t have memories from before you were born. You do have memories from most of the time after you were born.<br><br> So it would make sense—if this is a memory bias—that it turns on sometime near the moment of your birth. Obviously not exactly then, but this would explain why we don&#39;t see this for what people think about before they were born and after.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Does it really not matter how young you are? The stereotype is obviously, you know, Grandpa Simpson. It&#39;s like, older people are always talking about how things were better back then, but not necessarily younger people.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah; we totally expected to find that as well, and we didn&#39;t really. So when you ask people about the decline that they have perceived over their lifetimes, there&#39;s no difference in the decline that younger and older people perceive.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Julie, I was surprised to hear that there wasn&#39;t a difference between older people and younger people in terms of how they perceive this moral decline. I mean, you&#39;re not an old person; you&#39;re young. So do you remember ever having this feeling?<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> I distinctly remember I did not get a smartphone until I moved to DC in 2013. So in the years before that, when I lived in Chicago, I have a memory of having so many more interactions with strangers on the street.<br><br> And I definitely do not have those nearly as frequently anymore. And I think it&#39;s just because we&#39;re all looking at our phones, right? So part of me kind of romanticizes the, you know, chance encounters of the pre-smartphone era and all of that.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yeah. And when I hear you say that, I&#39;m like, <em>Oh, it&#39;s fine for Julie to have that feeling, and it&#39;s fine for me to have that feeling.</em> But if I multiply it by a few million times, then I get this political movement of “Let&#39;s go back to the era when things were better,” and that I don&#39;t really like so much.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Yeah. One thing that this makes me think of, too, is a line of research that has found that social trust has actually been declining in the US for decades. So people are essentially less and less likely to say that generally most other people can be trusted.<br><br> And so you&#39;re totally right that there are really big political implications for thinking the past was better and people used to be more trustworthy.<br><br> For me, it feels like kind of a chicken-or-an-egg question. Like, do we trust people less because we believe they&#39;ve gotten morally worse? Or do we believe people are worse because we&#39;re more disconnected from our communities?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> We focused here on a pretty narrow question, which is, “Has the way that people treat one another in their everyday lives changed over time?” And do people think that it has?<br><br> This is a model of when things are bad, it&#39;s easy for them to seem like they have gotten worse. And so I don&#39;t think this is the only domain where we might find this illusion, because people say this about a lot of different parts of life.<br><br> You know: that art is worse than it used to be. That culture is worse than it used to be. That the education system is worse than it used to be. But it seems pretty clear to me that we are predisposed to believe that it&#39;s true, even when it&#39;s not.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Your assumptions in this research are—people have this idea that a certain kind of morality has declined. But in your mind, it has not declined. So to you, this is like an illusion. I mean, you call it an illusion.正确的？<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yes.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Okay. So working within that assumption, what&#39;s your explanation? Like, why would a majority of us be operating under a delusion/illusion? Like something that <em>you&#39;re</em> saying is clearly not true.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> We think that there are two cognitive biases that can combine to produce this illusion. So this explanation has two parts. The first is what we call biased exposure, which is that people tend to attend to predominantly negative information, especially about people that they don&#39;t know.<br><br> So this is both a combination of the information that they receive about people that they don&#39;t know, which is primarily negative, and the information that they pay attention to. So this is why when you look out at the world beyond your personal world, it looks like it&#39;s full of people who are doing bad things. They&#39;re lying and cheating and stealing and killing.<br><br> The second part of the explanation is what we call biased memory. Memory researchers have noticed that the badness of bad memories tends to fade faster than the goodness of good memories.<br><br> So if you got turned down for your high-school prom, it feels pretty bad at the time. Twenty years later, it&#39;s maybe a funny story. If you have a great high-school prom, it feels pretty good at the time. And 20 years later, it&#39;s still a pretty nice memory. It doesn&#39;t feel as nice as it did to experience it, but it still feels pretty nice.<br><br> And that turns out to be, on average, what happens to people&#39;s memories: that the bad ones inch toward neutral faster than the good ones do, And the bad ones are more likely to both be forgotten and to become good in retrospect.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> So when I read the paper, Hanna, I wondered whether what might be going on is that people are, to some degree, picking up on a real change in the world.<br><br> There&#39;s the decline of social trust—but also widespread loneliness and disconnection and the erosion of community life, in the sense of fewer people knowing their neighbors and declining membership in community organizations.<br><br> And all of those things definitely have an impact on people&#39;s personal lives. But I think it manifests as a vague feeling like, <em>Oh, it&#39;s just harder to make friends or harder to feel like I&#39;m a part of my community.</em><br><br> So I wonder if we&#39;re feeling this sort of vague and troubling sense of disconnection and assigning it a false explanation: that things used to be better before, and people just suck more than they used to.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Oh, that&#39;s really interesting. So what you&#39;re saying is the feeling is real. Like, the feeling that something has changed is real because something <em>has</em> changed. There is more disconnection and loneliness.<br><br> So instead we make up this very tidy story. Like, “When I was a kid, things were better and people were nicer and the mailman tipped his hat”—and we just kind of stopped there.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Yeah; there definitely are real things that are really happening that would make people feel disconnected from strangers around them. And I wonder if, yeah, we just have a hard time psychologically, knowing why that&#39;s the case.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> So Adam, I want to run a couple of theories by you. One is the possibility that something has actually changed. And we&#39;re just calling it by the wrong name. That, like, something has declined. And this is from a different body of psychological research about social trust.<br><br> That there is a change in our isolation, our sense of connectedness, our face-to-ace contact. Like there are some societal changes which are real and structural and have kind of left a hole in us that we are misnaming <em>morality</em> .<br><br> When we read it here, we thought there are some things that are changing and that do leave us a little despairing—and maybe we&#39;re just calling them by the wrong name.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Like we have this incredibly powerful feeling that something is wrong, and that “something” is connectedness or community or something like that.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah. So it&#39;s very easy to slip from “People are less kind than they used to be” to <em>“Things</em> are worse than they used to be.” And so it is true that trust in institutions has declined over time. A lot of people also say that interpersonal trust has declined over time. And I actually think that case is much more overstated than the decline in institutional trust.<br><br> There&#39;s some work by a guy named Richard Eibach on how people think the world has gotten more dangerous. And he finds that people believe this. And the people who believe this, especially, are parents. And when you ask those parents “When did the world become more dangerous?,” you get a date that is curiously close to the date of the birth of their first child.<br><br> The obvious implication being that nothing about the world changed. It was your worldview that changed. And now you have to, you know, protect this fragile life—and so you are much more attuned to the dangers of the world. That&#39;s why you think there&#39;s more of them.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> You know, Julie, I have this conversation with my brother all the time, and he&#39;s always telling me his kids aren&#39;t safe. He lives in New York. He&#39;s like, “My kids aren&#39;t safe. They can&#39;t go outside. They can&#39;t go down the block.” Like, he really freaks out, you know? And: “It&#39;s way less safe than it was when we were kids.” And I&#39;m like, “Dude, we grew up in New York in the &#39;70s, right?” It was really not safe.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Like, statistically.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Statistically. And I&#39;ve shown him news articles, and I once pulled out an FBI report. I specially downloaded an FBI report that showed, you know, crime statistics in New York from when we were kids.<br><br> And his conviction is so strong about this. I can&#39;t budge him. I can&#39;t show him enough numbers or statistics to make him think, <em>Oh, things aren&#39;t worse now</em> .<br><br> I mean, Adam Mastroianni actually has a term for this. This is a little mean to my brother, but his term is <em>unearned conviction</em> . And I think what he means by that is exactly this. It&#39;s like: Your conviction is incredibly strong, even though you have really no basis to back up the story that you&#39;re attaching to that very strong conviction.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Yeah. I mean it seems like, regardless of the FBI report, the story your brother is telling himself is super-emotionally resonant.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yes.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> And the stories that we tell ourselves about our own lives really do sort of shape who we are. It&#39;s really interesting, because when we tell these stories to ourselves about our personal lives, a lot of times those stories fall into one of two categories. One being redemptive and the other being contamination.<br><br> And so a redemptive story is like: “I have suffered through these trials and come out stronger for it, and things are looking up.” Whereas a contamination story is like: “These trials have conquered me, and I am now broken and fundamentally a worse person.”<br><br> And it probably won&#39;t surprise you to hear that contamination sequences are not great for people&#39;s mental health. That research was done with stories that we&#39;re telling about our personal lives. But it feels like we&#39;re kind of telling a contamination story about all of humanity.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> I guess what&#39;s depressing to me is: Why are those the ones that stick? I mean, there are redemption stories that are popular in American society.<br><br> But I feel like in a lot of moments in history, and now is one of them, these contamination stories—like “America was great once” or “Russia was great once”—have a particular kind of emotional juice and can really rally people.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Yeah. I mean, maybe it&#39;s kind of like your brother&#39;s fear in New York, right? Where it&#39;s just like—that is so viscerally emotional. It&#39;s the safety of your kid. And so, of course, that&#39;s going to have like a way stronger impact.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Now Adam, did you find any appreciable differences between demographics? So if not between old and young people, what about gender differences, or people with different political ideologies?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> We didn&#39;t find any gender differences. We didn&#39;t find any differences by racial groups. We didn&#39;t find any education differences. The only other demographic difference that we found was an ideological one, a political one. The people who self-identified as more conservative perceived more decline over time than the people who self-identified as liberal.<br><br> But even for the people who were the most liberal, they still said that people are less kind today than they were 10 years ago, 20 years ago, or whatever point in the past. So this is something that conservatives said louder, but liberals said as well.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> So someone who identifies as a liberal could believe that there&#39;s less racism and sexism—but still believe that those other general universal markers of morality have declined.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yes. And in fact, it seems like they do. In our studies, the much smaller group of people who say that people are better now than they used to be—when we asked them “Why? What were you thinking of?,” one thing that does come up for them is there&#39;s more tolerance. There&#39;s less racism, sexism, ableism; all the <em>isms</em> .<br><br> So it seems like that&#39;s not what people are spontaneously thinking of when they say that people are less kind than they used to be. Because if you ask them directly, “Do you think that, for instance, people treat African Americans with more respect and courtesy or less than in the past?,” a majority of people will say more today than in the past.<br><br> But if you ask them, “Are people more or less kind today?,” they&#39;ll go less kind. So this is not what they&#39;re thinking of when they answer the question.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Yeah. So it&#39;s a really, really specific feeling. I definitely think that people treat each other with more respect, largely because we have broadened the window of who is allowed to be respected, and sort of patriarchal notions of control over people&#39;s bodies and who gets to make decisions. I mean, there&#39;s so many ways in which we have opened the door to fairness and equity. I&#39;d much rather be alive today than 50 years ago, for sure.<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah, I agree. And so I think it was especially surprising that I&#39;m sure there are many other people who agree. But even some of the people who do agree—they seem to think like, <em>Yeah, but that actually doesn&#39;t come from people&#39;s heart of hearts</em> . That they&#39;re actually still worse to one another now than they used to be.<br><br> Yeah; they&#39;ll say all the right things or they&#39;ll have the right opinions. But you know, they won&#39;t hold the door open for you, or they&#39;ll cheat you when they can. Now people know the right things to say, but they still <em>do</em> more of the bad things.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Do we feel the same way with people we know? Does it play out differently in our personal lives?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> You can actually also produce an illusion of improvement. You actually primarily hear good things and experience good things about people that you know. And so we thought that in your personal world, this illusion of decline might be turned down or turned off or even reversed.<br><br> And people told us: “People in general? Worse today than they were 15 years ago. People that I have known for the last 15 years? Better today than they were 15 years ago.”<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> So Julie, one thing that Adam found that I thought was so interesting was that people we know—like our own people, people we&#39;re close to or whatever—they&#39;re somehow getting better over time, and yet the general public are getting worse. I don&#39;t quite understand how those fit together.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> So I guess we just think the moral decline is happening with strangers, with all those <em>other</em> people.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Right.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> And it seems like potentially the disconnection from community that many people are experiencing could just mean that we&#39;re slotting more people into the “morally compromised, untrustworthy” category.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> Right. Like, if we met more people and we had more casual acquaintances and we went to our bowling leagues or whatever, then we might include more people in that circle of people we know. And those people are good people. So that could sort of spiral upward rather than what&#39;s happening, which is a momentum downward.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Adam&#39;s study kind of seems to say that if you get to know people, then you won&#39;t think they&#39;re on a downward slope of moral depravity anymore.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> For one thing, Adam, it sounds to me like the problem is that people are absolutely certain. Like they&#39;re not questioning. Was the past a worse place? It&#39;s a sort of lack of humility. Because if you try to understand, “Well, maybe what did get worse?,” then you would come up with more specific and useful policy solutions.<br><br> I mean, I assume one reason you did this research is to point out a mistake. Like, we&#39;re all living under this delusion. And in your head—since you sound like a fairly optimistic person—is it “knowledge is power,” and people will know, and then they will stop? What&#39;s the aim, or what&#39;s your wish here?<br><br> <strong>Mastroianni:</strong> Yeah. I mean, as a psychologist I a little bit despair of changing people&#39;s minds, because I know how difficult it is. It doesn&#39;t work the way that we think that it works, like, “Oh, you have the wrong model of the world. How about I give you the correct facts, and now you have the correct model of the world?” When does that ever happen? When has that ever happened to me? Like, never.<br><br> And one effect that I certainly hope that this has is: Whenever politicians or aspiring politicians make the claim that, you know, “Things used to be better, and put me in charge and I&#39;ll make them better again”—that&#39;s a very old thing that we&#39;ve heard many times. And it resonates with us, perhaps because we are primed to believe it, even when it&#39;s not true.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> So, Hanna, now that we know this is an illusion, right, that&#39;s very interesting. But will it actually change how you feel?<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> I don&#39;t really know. I mean, I feel like as a journalist, it depresses me a little bit because I spent a lot of time researching and marshaling facts, like I did with my brother. And to think that emotions ultimately squash all of that—I don&#39;t really know what to do with that.<br><br> <strong>Beck:</strong> Yeah.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> But in my own personal life, awareness is helpful. I don&#39;t think any bad can come from understanding your own emotional levers better. It&#39;s not that it immediately leads to a change, but I don&#39;t think it can ever be bad to understand, <em>Oh, I&#39;m having this emotional attachment or strong belief, and that&#39;s leading me to behave in this way.</em> That in and of itself is a small daily miracle. So that&#39;s good enough.<br><br> <strong>Rosin:</strong> <em>Listeners, if you enjoyed this conversation with Adam Mastroianni and Julie Beck, and if you generally like learning about these psychological levers that are guiding our choices, Julie hosts a full season of conversations much like this one, on the Atlantic podcast</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/how-to-build-a-happy-life/">How to Talk to People</a> . <em>You can find it wherever you listen to podcasts.</em><br><br> This episode was produced by Becca Rashid. Edited by Jocelyn Frank. Fact-checked by Isabel Cristo. Engineering by Rob Smierciak. The executive producer of audio is Claudine Ebeid. The managing editor of audio is Andrea Valdez. You can find new episodes of <em>Radio Atlantic</em> every Thursday.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/archive/2023/07/are-you-plagued-by-the-feeling-that-everyone-used-to-be-nicer/674838/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/podcasts/archive/2023/07/are-you-plagued-by-the-feeling-that-everyone-used-to-be-nicer/674838/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[No One Deserves to Go to Harvard]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> But the only people who have to feel bad about “unearned access” are the beneficiaries of affirmative action. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/EM_uthtf-vG0KzoYSRl6XBXt7Tg=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/harvard/original.jpg" alt="插图显示哈佛毕业礼服，但穿着它的人是看不见的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo-illustration by Joanne Imperio / The Atlantic. Source: Getty.</figcaption></figure> No one <em>deserves</em> a seat at Harvard, but only some people are supposed to feel bad about the one they get.<br><br> Last month, the Supreme Court ruled that race-based affirmative action violated the equal-protection clause, spurring a news cycle about the admissions advantages conferred on certain people of color. The preferential admissions treatment that racial minorities received is just one bonus among many, however. A <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://opportunityinsights.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/CollegeAdmissions_Paper.pdf">new study</a> from the economic research group Opportunity Insights quantifies the advantages of wealth in higher education: The ultra rich are much likelier to gain admission to elite colleges than anyone else, even when controlling for academic success. Put another way, if you take a room full of 18-year-olds with the same SAT or ACT score, those from the top 1 percent are 55 percent more likely to be admitted than middle-class applicants. Those from the top 0.1 percent are 150 percent more likely to get in.<br><br> For decades, underrepresented minorities have faced accusations of unearned access. The implication of these resentments has always been that some people who deserve to go to Harvard have had their spots “taken” by Black, Latino, and Native American students who, absent efforts to tip the scales in their favor, would never have been granted admission. But no one “deserves” to gain admission anywhere. No university can construct a perfectly meritocratic system. How should an admissions program distinguish among tens of thousands of standout students fairly? Is publishing a best-selling novel more important than a perfect GPA? If a student with a mediocre GPA but a perfect SAT score explains their academic deficiency by pointing out that they were taking care of their sick parent, is it reasonable for an admissions officer to consider them more “meritorious” than a student with perfect grades <em>and</em> scores?<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/raj-chetty-paper-harvard-ivy-league-elite/674803/">Annie Lowrey: Why you have to care about these 12 colleges</a><br><br> Any method of distinguishing among such applicants is inherently subjective, and any of the traits, acquired skills, or backgrounds that help push students over the edge could be considered “unearned advantage.” But none of those carries the stigma that race-based affirmative action does. The whispers of affirmative action never leave the people of color who enter into elite spaces; they become the targets of resentment for the unfulfilled ambitions of their fellow students and, later on, their colleagues.<br><br> A 1995 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/affirm/stories/aa032495.htm">dispatch</a> from <em>The Washington Post</em> highlights these resentments: “They talk about a glass ceiling for women and minorities. There&#39;s a glass ceiling for middle-aged white male managers too,” a 52-year-old worker living in Georgia tells the reporters. Another man aptly addresses the zero-sum nature of the conflict: “Why should I suffer so they can have a better chance in jobs or anything for that matter.”<br><br> Or take this monologue from <em>The West Wing</em> ’s CJ Cregg about why she&#39;s “the wrong Democrat” to defend affirmative action: “After my father fought in Korea, he became what this government begs every college graduate to become. He became a teacher. And he raised a family on a teacher&#39;s salary, and he paid his taxes and always crossed at the green. And any time there was an opportunity for career advancement, it took him an extra five years because invariably there was a less qualified Black woman in the picture. So instead of retiring as superintendent of the Ohio Valley Union Free School District, he retired head of the math department at William Henry Harrison Junior High.”<br><br> CJ thinks her father hit a glass ceiling put in place by a “less qualified Black woman,” a common villain in these stories of stunted careers.<br><br> Affirmative action is an albatross, whereas other forms of unearned privilege are, if anything, a sign of belonging. Most legacy kids don&#39;t try to hide their ancestral claims; they are proud of them, and so are their parents, who come to campus decked in university apparel. A Class of &#39;87 cap screams status far more loudly than an earnest “Proud Parent of …” T-shirt. Nor do the kids who row crew or play lacrosse conceal their participation in these résumé-padding pastimes. Later on in life, they eagerly share that they once rowed for Stanford.<br><br> This isn&#39;t just about the top 1 percent or even 10 percent. In a system that requires subjective discrimination, <em>no one</em> is objectively best qualified. Men have a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/07/30/achieving-perfect-gender-balance-on-campus-isnt-that-important-ending-private-colleges-affirmative-action-for-men-is/">much easier time getting into elite schools than women.</a> According to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2015/3/26/regional-diversity-scrutiny/"><em>The Harvard Crimson</em></a> , 51.5 percent of the noninternational students in the class of 2018 came from New York, New Jersey, California, or Massachusetts. Living in the United States is a form of unearned privilege as well; a genius in Ethiopia is less likely than the rich failson of an American lawyer to gain admission to one of our universities. It is perfectly legitimate for Americans to want our institutions to discriminate in our favor, but let&#39;s not pretend, then, that this is some fine-tuned exercise in picking the best and the brightest. The point is that we accept some forms of unearned advantage but not others. Born the son of a Harvard-educated lawyer who lives in Massachusetts? Fine. Born Black? Unacceptable.<br><br> In 2022, the linguist John McWhorter, who opposes both racial and legacy preferences in admissions processes, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/02/01/opinion/affirmative-action.html">wrote</a> in <em>The New York Times</em> that “however unfair it may be, legacy admissions do not reflect on white students or white people, broadly speaking, in the same way [as affirmative action does on Black people].” McWhorter skips right over <em>why</em> even as he refers to legacy preferences as an “embarrassment” for universities.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/04/ban-legacy-college-admissions-nepotism/629566/">Richard V. Reeves: The shame deficit</a><br><br> But preferential treatment for legacies and the elite isn&#39;t embarrassing. The reason race-based affirmative action is not treated the same way as all of the other unearned advantages is because of the presumption that racial minorities don&#39;t belong in elite spaces. Elite people belong at Ivies. So do men. So do Americans. So do people who play water polo. So do flute players and the children of alumni. The unearned advantages we accept are the ones we have already decided are acceptable characteristics of the elite.<br><br> Could the Supreme Court&#39;s decision finally convince the general public that the Black students who <em>are</em> admitted belong?我对此表示怀疑。 Jon Wang is one of the students who joined the plaintiffs in their successful effort to end race-conscious admissions. He <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.kron4.com/news/bay-area/asian-american-student-claims-affirmative-action-prevented-his-admissions-but-california-law-doesnt-allow-that/">blames</a> affirmative action for his rejection from a number of schools. Among them: UC Berkeley. That university has been legally prohibited from considering race and ethnicity in admissions since the late 1990s, a change that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://cshe.berkeley.edu/publications/affirmative-action-mismatch-and-economic-mobility-after-california%E2%80%99s-proposition-209">significantly drove down admissions</a> of underrepresented minorities across the University of California system.<br><br> The sooner we accept that no one <em>deserves</em> to be an elite, the better. Should a handful of private institutions benefiting from billions of dollars in taxpayer subsidies and tax breaks and other public monies get to select our political, economic, and cultural leaders behind closed doors? Sure, it&#39;s better if they do so without employing harmful racial stereotypes. Better still if they stop putting their thumbs on the scale for the top 0.1 percent. But fighting over the appropriate racial composition of the future white-collar lawyers and corporate consultants of America only legitimizes the enterprise to begin with.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 13:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/harvard-admissions-affirmative-action-elite-colleges/674837/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/harvard-admissions-affirmative-action-elite-colleges/674837/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[‘It’s Really First-Class Work’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Watching <em>Oppenheimer</em> with Richard Rhodes, who wrote a definitive account of the Manhattan Project <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/ila2DFKZYfKS9SJaSGJ3aKgB8OE=/0x83:1594x980/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/oppenheimer_inline_1/original.jpg" alt="希里安·墨菲 (Cillian Murphy) 在电影《奥本海默》中饰演 J·罗伯特·奥本海默" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Melinda Sue Gordon / Universal Pictures</figcaption></figure> <strong><em>This article containers spoilers for the film</em> Oppenheimer.</strong><br><br> Few authors have written as insightfully about the life of J. Robert Oppenheimer as Richard Rhodes, whose 1986 book, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-making-of-the-atomic-bomb-richard-rhodes/9781451677614?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>The Making of the Atomic Bomb</em></a> , is widely regarded as the definitive account of the Manhattan Project. Rhodes&#39;s comprehensive history, which won a Pulitzer Prize, is both a massive work of scholarship—the main text alone runs nearly 800 pages—and a literary feat that he conceived as “the tragic epic of the twentieth century.” Over the years, according to Rhodes, it has been optioned many times, but no film or television version has ever been made. “It&#39;s quite obvious why,” Rhodes told me. “It&#39;s just too big a story.”<br><br> Over the weekend, along with millions of other moviegoers, Rhodes saw <em>Oppenheimer</em> , Christopher Nolan&#39;s three-hour biopic of the physicist known as the father of the atomic bomb. The next day, curious about his reaction, I spoke with Rhodes by phone. He was deeply impressed by the film, especially in light of earlier attempts to adapt the same material. “It&#39;s really first-class work,” Rhodes said, comparing it favorably with Roland Joffé&#39;s <em>Fat Man and Little Boy</em> (“badly done,” from a technological perspective) and specifically praising Cillian Murphy&#39;s performance in the title role. “If anything, he was a little too confident. But Oppenheimer was pretty confident.”<br><br> We also discussed aspects of the story that weren&#39;t covered by the film, which Nolan adapted from <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/books-briefing-kai-bird/674785/">the biography <em>American Prometheus</em></a> , by Kai Bird and Martin J. Sherwin. Given its relentless concentration on Oppenheimer, the movie necessarily leaves a lot out, including plenty of what Rhodes called “drama on the industrial side” and the perspectives of scientists and victims who fall outside its protagonist&#39;s circle of consciousness. For the rest, viewers may need to return to Rhodes&#39;s own wide-ranging work, which expands beyond even the largest IMAX screen.<br><br> <em>This conversation has been edited for length and clarity.</em><br><br> <strong>Alec Nevala-Lee:</strong> Do you think that the film&#39;s picture of Oppenheimer is accurate?<br><br> <strong>Richard Rhodes:</strong> One time I asked [the physicist] Bob Serber if my portrait of Oppenheimer was anywhere close to the real human being. And Serber, who had a very dry wit, said, “It&#39;s the least wrong of all those I&#39;ve seen.”<br><br> And I think that applies here, because the difficult edges to Oppenheimer were, to some degree, sanded off. But there have been several Oppenheimers in past versions. The BBC did a series with Sam Waterston. He was wonderful, but he was much too nice. Then when the next version [the 2009 PBS docudrama <em>The Trials of J. Robert Oppenheimer</em> ] came around, [David Strathairn] played Oppenheimer as a hand-wringing neurotic, which really pissed me off when I watched it. You could not possibly have someone who did what Oppenheimer did in his life who was just sitting around shaking all the time with anxiety.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-review-christopher-nolan/674749/">Read: <em>Oppenheimer</em> is more than a creation myth about the atomic bomb</a><br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> Most viewers are probably encountering figures such as Lewis Strauss (the government official who orchestrated the notorious hearing that revoked Oppenheimer&#39;s security clearance, played by Robert Downey Jr. in a towering performance) and Leslie Groves (the military head of the atomic-weapons program, played by Matt Damon) for the first time.<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> Yeah, I think Strauss, if anything, was depicted somewhat more pleasantly than he really was. I think he was even more nasty. And I was really surprised by Matt Damon, who did a damn good job. In fact, it gave me a different sort of perspective on Groves. I had pictured him as stuffier than he was depicted here, and I think this is probably closer to the truth. Groves was really a superb leader, and also anxious and insecure around the scientists. Which was a funny combination, because he drove them to get the job done anyway.<br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> Was there anything else about the movie that surprised you?<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> Mostly minor things. I&#39;d read about the arrival of the shock wave after the light [from the Trinity test], but my God—when you see it in IMAX, it really hits you; it resonates in your chest. We were just knocked back in our chairs. I wish [Edward] Teller [Oppenheimer&#39;s nemesis in the debate over the hydrogen bomb] had been a little different. I spent an interesting 30 minutes with Teller and had some sense of what he was like. That guy [Benny Safdie] was a little too oily, not quite as sinister as Teller really was.<br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> Nolan has always struck me as a pretty cerebral guy who also makes movies on the largest possible scale. It tracks to me that Oppenheimer, a theorist who found himself in charge of this incredible industrial operation, would appeal to him.<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> That makes sense. My experience with writing books is, your best books are the ones that you have a deep emotional investment in. And there&#39;s an automatic tendency when you&#39;re writing a biography to turn the character in the biography into oneself.<br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> Nolan, who is willing to play with structure, seems like a good choice for this story, because it allows him to deliver so much information. He can cut between the Manhattan Project period, the Oppenheimer hearing, and the hearing for Strauss&#39;s nomination as secretary of commerce, and use the dynamic to explain things to the audience.<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> I had never thought about the parallel between Strauss and Oppenheimer before, but the story is structured so that both of them are destroyed by the forces of Washington, DC And that&#39;s really a wonderful sort of parallel. Oppenheimer&#39;s kind of a tragic hero, and I wouldn&#39;t give that credit to someone like Strauss. But in a kind of corrupt way, he followed the same arc across his life. That was a real insight that I haven&#39;t seen—maybe it&#39;s in the biography [ <em>American Prometheus</em> ].<br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> I read it recently, and Strauss&#39;s hearing takes up just a single paragraph. But Nolan decides to make it a fifth of the movie, for the reasons you&#39;re saying. There&#39;s this fascinating parallel that is possible only in a movie—the thematic echoes and the rhythm of the editing provide a sense of closure that would be much more difficult in book form.<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> You can do that, but you&#39;d have to have that insight. And Nolan had that insight. When you do research for a book, often you&#39;ll come across something that can be expanded upon. When I was working on <em>The Making of the Atomic Bomb</em> , I read a history of the development of physics in the United States. And in a footnote at the end of a chapter deep in the book, there&#39;s this note about [Enrico] Fermi, one day going up to the window and looking down at the gray winter length of Manhattan Island—alive with crowds—and cupping his hands together and saying, “A little bomb like that and it would all disappear.” The historian who wrote this book threw that away into a footnote. I made it the end of the whole first third of my book.<br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> The movie for the most part is very realistic, but dreamlike moments visualize Oppenheimer&#39;s psychological state, which reminded me of your book. The opening paragraph starts with the physicist Leo Szilard—whom you use in your book as a “clothesline” character, someone the audience can follow across a complex narrative—crossing the street, with a description of what the weather was like in London, and then it ends with a passage out of John Milton. And that elevates the tone in a way that tells you something about the material.<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> That&#39;s what I was trying to do, of course. But I thought it was really off tone when [Nolan, in one of those dream sequences] had Oppenheimer and Jean Tatlock screwing on the table in the security hearing. That was, I think, maybe a bit of an overreach. It&#39;s curious and interesting that they decided not to visit Hiroshima.<br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> I was wondering whether Nolan would show that, but every scene that&#39;s not about Strauss is from Oppenheimer&#39;s point of view. So instead of the bombing, you see him waiting for a phone call, because he has no control over how the weapon is used. There&#39;s an earlier scene where the characters talk about saving lives by heading off an American invasion of Japan. Is this something that would have been discussed before the bombing, or is this a rationalization that defenders of the decision arrived at after the fact?<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> Well, George Marshall [the US Army chief of staff during World War II] said we knew that the Japanese were getting their people trained to fight us. And we thought that if we could bomb the beaches with atomic bombs, we might shock the Japanese into surrender. In fact, there were plans to keep going. I found a memorandum from Oppenheimer to Groves saying if we make a design that uses both plutonium and uranium, we can have six bombs a month by October.<br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> If the movie had included that suggestion, it would have really changed the viewer&#39;s sense of Oppenheimer.<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> There was also discussion in &#39;43 or &#39;44 of making radiation bombs stuffed with cobalt 60 or something that would just spread radioactive particles all over the place. We did some tests down in New Mexico, and I remember someone&#39;s comment afterward—it was the most god-awful stuff you could imagine. Which, yes, it would be, wouldn&#39;t it?<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/richard-rhodes-making-of-the-atomic-bomb-ai/674777/">Read: The real lesson from <em>The Making of the Atomic Bomb</em></a><br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> I recently watched the opera <em>Doctor Atomic</em> , where one character is Oppenheimer&#39;s Native American maid. That&#39;s the kind of voice you don&#39;t hear in the movie.<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> It was certainly a valid perspective. These guys came in and swept the mesa clean, and they used the Native American people to clean their houses.<br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> Nolan is so focused on Oppenheimer—but with a movie like this, you have to find, as you&#39;ve said, the clothesline.<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> And there was so much drama on the industrial side that&#39;s basically just left out. It&#39;s compressed into something that is really very brilliant—those big open jars in which they keep dropping marbles [to track the supply of uranium and plutonium]. That&#39;s as close as we come to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/05/the-60-year-downfall-of-nuclear-power-in-the-us-has-left-a-huge-mess/560945/">seeing the Hanford complex</a> , with its huge production reactors, or the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2013/12/what-was-once-the-worlds-largest-building-has-now-been-completely-demolished/282549/">Oak Ridge complex</a> , with one factory that was [about] a mile long, so the supervisors inside rode around on bicycles.<br><br> <strong>Nevala-Lee:</strong> How do you feel about the impact this movie will have on how a mass audience understands this immensely complicated story?<br><br> <strong>Rhodes:</strong> I&#39;ve been living with this story now for 40, 50 years. So what I&#39;m most excited by—you will consider this crass, but this is where I am in my life—is we&#39;ve got an option from a German company for <em>The Making of the Atomic Bomb</em> to be made into a multipart television series. And I&#39;m just hoping that this will cause enough stir that these people will finally, for the first time in all these years, actually pick up the option. That would be just wonderful, and I&#39;d pay off my mortgage, and my version of the story would be out there.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 13:11:08 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-richard-rhodes-interview/674828/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-richard-rhodes-interview/674828/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel Has Already Lost]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Israel hasn&#39;t destroyed its democracy yet. But something similarly essential is already gone. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Vt_bWWHSvbG_s-HSKPKAVU7Cuo4=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/israel-1/original.jpg" alt="以色列抗议活动照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Corinna Kern / Reuters</figcaption></figure> In March, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/03/israel-protests-judicial-system-overhaul-netanyahu/673530/">unprecedented outcry</a> compelled Israel&#39;s government to pause its attempted overhaul of the country&#39;s judiciary. But the reprieve was only temporary. At the time, the far-right ministers <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/03/27/netanyahu-israeli-judicial-overhaul-suspend-protests">Itamar Ben-Gvir</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-says-hes-delaying-overhaul-to-allow-dialogue-but-vows-reform-will-happen/">Bezalel Smotrich</a> assured supporters that the reforms would pass by late July.<br><br> This did not happen. Instead, on Monday, in the final week of the Israeli Parliament&#39;s summer session, the ruling coalition passed the least significant component of its proposed legislation: curtailing the Supreme Court&#39;s ability to use the “reasonableness standard” when reviewing government decisions. Contrary to the far right&#39;s pledge, the government did not enact its plan to subordinate the appointment of Supreme Court judges to politicians. Nor did it grant the coalition the ability to override judicial decisions.<br><br> In other words, Israel&#39;s democracy—flawed as it is—remains intact, for now. Far from incapacitated, the country&#39;s highest court is already <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/high-court-justices-rush-back-from-abroad-to-hear-petitions-against-reasonableness/">rushing</a> to convene an unprecedented session to rule on the legality of this week&#39;s effort to curb its powers. But whether or not Israel erodes its democratic guardrails in the months ahead, its people have already lost something similarly essential: basic social trust.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/israel-protests-netanyahu-judicial-systems-overhaul/673623/">Yair Rosenberg: The three biggest misconceptions about Israel&#39;s upheaval</a><br><br> Israel&#39;s warring camps are ostensibly fighting over the reasonableness doctrine, a technical tool inherited from British common law that allows the country&#39;s high court to overrule certain government decisions, though not legislation. But fundamentally, this debate is not about the law itself, which few Israelis could easily explain. It is about whose judgment is trusted to safeguard the country&#39;s democracy.<br><br> Put crudely, the reasonableness doctrine is a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/the-reason-for-reasonableness-a-doctrine-at-the-heart-of-the-overhaul-explained/">subjective standard</a> that has allowed Israel&#39;s justices to substitute their own considerations for the legislature&#39;s when assessing the merits of certain government actions and civil-service appointments. Given that the members of Israel&#39;s Supreme Court are appointed by a panel composed mostly of other judges and lawyers, a credible case exists for restraining this capacity, which lacks democratic accountability.<br><br> But this week&#39;s reform did not take place in a vacuum. It took place in the context of a power grab by the most hard-right government in Israeli history—one that received only <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://votes25.bechirot.gov.il/">48.4 percent</a> of the vote in the last election. If Israel&#39;s judges no longer get to decide which administrative decisions are “reasonable,” that means that the politicians in power do, even if they, too, lack a mandate. And today, those politicians include <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/maoz-set-to-rejoin-government-resume-role-as-jewish-identity-czar/">homophobes</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jpost.com/israel/ben-gvir-convicted-of-inciting-to-racism">convicted</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/article-728898">criminals</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jpost.com/israel-elections/analysis-why-is-religious-zionist-politician-dreaming-of-galactic-state-597867">aspiring theocrats</a> , and proud <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/i-made-mistakes-ben-gvir-tells-high-court-hes-refined-since-entering-politics/">nationalist</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-should-wipe-out-palestinian-town-of-huwara-says-senior-minister-smotrich/">chauvinists</a> .<br><br> Polls <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/poll-only-1-in-4-israelis-wants-government-to-press-ahead-with-judicial-overhaul/">consistently</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/AnshelPfeffer/status/1683912208307085321">show</a> that two-thirds of Israel&#39;s citizens oppose the ruling coalition&#39;s unilateral overhaul of the judiciary. Put another way, most Israelis simply do not trust the intentions of their own government. They do not believe that Netanyahu, let alone <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2022/12/israel-election-bibi-netanyahu-ben-gvir/672572/">the extremist allies he depends upon</a> to maintain his power, will be more reasonable than the unelected Supreme Court. And they do not believe that the coalition will stop with this small salvo against the judiciary when it has already announced its intentions to deconstruct the entire edifice. The Israeli opposition has lost faith in its countrymen to act in the best interest of the entire nation, which is why its leaders now <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/GLZRadio/status/1683697314509082625">openly accuse</a> the government of seeking to destroy democracy.<br><br> This rancor extends well beyond the usual partisan politics, and it runs both ways. Rather than attempting to calm the waters and reestablish civic trust, Netanyahu&#39;s far-right ministers have rubbed their recent victory in the opposition&#39;s face and promised more of the same. “The salad bar is open,” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/politics-and-diplomacy/article-752065">crowed</a> Ben-Gvir on Saturday night, framing the impending reasonableness reform as merely the appetizer for a much more forbidding buffet. A cannier, more responsible politician would mouth platitudes about how <i>This is a difficult time for Israel, but we are all patriots who want the best for one another and the country.</i> Ben-Gvir does not believe that—and rarely feels compelled to pretend that he does. Instead, he and his allies <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/liveblog_entry/us-envoy-nides-says-claims-that-us-is-funding-protests-in-israel-are-absurd/">have</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/itamarbengvir/status/1683706154986135552">cast</a> the hundreds of thousands of anti-overhaul street protesters as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/2023-03-10/ty-article-magazine/.premium/why-netanyahu-slurs-israels-pro-democracy-protesters-as-anarchists/00000186-c637-d069-a3df-c63ffad90000">“privileged anarchists”</a> and foreign-funded enemies, rather than fellow citizens expressing genuine concern. Something has gone terribly wrong in a country where this is how leaders speak about those they are supposed to shepherd.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/03/israel-judicial-reform-supreme-court-protests-tel-aviv/673414/">Michael Oren: Israel&#39;s tectonic struggle</a><br><br> Such an utter collapse of shared solidarity is unprecedented in Israeli history, which is why what happens next is so uncertain. In the days ahead, Israel&#39;s Supreme Court may overturn this first strike against its authority, something it has never done before to a quasi-constitutional “basic law” of this kind. The justices may let the legislation stand but interpret it into irrelevance, coming up with new legal ways to get to the same results that the reasonableness doctrine previously provided. Or the Court may punt entirely, deciding that it lacks the power to overrule such a parliamentary prerogative.<br><br> If the Court does undo this decision, it may stall the overhaul, throwing the coalition into chaos and recrimination. Or the reversal may galvanize the far-right&#39;s efforts to pass its entire anti-judicial package, by affirming its belief that small-scale changes will never be enough to change the Court&#39;s jurisprudence. There is a reason, after all, that the right&#39;s original plan included many more components than what has been passed: Removing reasonableness from the judicial toolbox still leaves the rest of the tools, not to mention those who wield them.<br><br> In the long run, the current coalition may use further legislation to cement its power, quash the courts, and marginalize its opposition. Or Netanyahu&#39;s government, which is already <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/2023-07-25/ty-article/post-judicial-coup-election-polls-give-gantz-30-seats-netanyahus-govt-losing-majority/00000189-8e3a-d4ba-a3e9-ce3fb50a0000">polling poorly</a> , may be crushed by the consequences of its own body blows to Israel&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-25-2023/card/israeli-stocks-shekel-fall-amid-political-and-economic-tumult-oStoKuWQfvDypNBKN7k4">economy</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/idf-says-battle-readiness-weeks-from-being-impacted-as-reservists-decamp-en-masse/">security</a> , and internal cohesion, much as the ill-fated <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ft.com/content/e4a95eac-71bc-4da9-b029-200764179d0c">economic overhaul</a> of British Prime Minister Liz Truss precipitated her exit. The fall of the reasonableness doctrine is the pebble that begins the avalanche, and the thing about avalanches is that they cannot be controlled.<br><br> Still, though the ultimate outcome of this week&#39;s events remains in limbo, one thing is certain: Regardless of whether Israel loses its independent judiciary, it has already lost a core component of any functioning democracy—the sense of collective concern among citizens. And that is something that cannot be fixed by any legislation or court order.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 11:38:58 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-supreme-court-netanyahu-parliament/674833/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-supreme-court-netanyahu-parliament/674833/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Fatigue Can Shatter a Person]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>日常疲劳与长期感染新冠肺炎和 ME/CFS 的人所经历的疲惫症状完全不同。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/SqDS3hCbD_cNzZNbluJmARrKoXY=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/long_covid_fatigue_maria_medem/original.jpg" alt="一位红衣女子坐在夕阳前，蓝衣跑步者在星星和月亮下从她身边飞驰而过。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>玛丽亚·梅德姆</figcaption></figure><small><i data-stringify-type="italic">This article was featured in One Story to Read Today, a newsletter in which our editors recommend a single must-read from</i> The Atlantic <i data-stringify-type="italic">, Monday through Friday.</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Sign up for it here.</a></i></small><br><br>亚历克西斯·米斯科 (Alexis Misko) 的健康状况已经有了很大改善，每月一次，她可以离开家几个小时。首先，她需要在黑暗的房间里躺上两天的大部分时间来增强能量，除了听有声读物之外什么也做不了。然后她需要一个司机、一个可以让她躺下的安静目的地，以及随后几天的休息时间来恢复。她告诉我，短暂的户外快乐“永远感觉不够”，但这比她在长期新冠疫情第一年所经历的要多得多，当时她不能直立一个多小时，也不能站立超过一个小时。 10分钟。现在，至少，她可以在洗澡的同一天看电视。<br><br>前世，她在研究生院熬夜，在医院担任职业治疗师，辛苦轮班。她进行长距离跑步，并在长途飞行后下垂。这一切都无法与她自三年前感染 COVID-19 以来所经历的一切相比。她在一封电子邮件中告诉我，她现在感受到的疲劳“就像你的本质和你的生命力完全耗尽”。<br><br>疲劳是新冠肺炎长期症状中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thelancet.com/journals/eclinm/article/PIIS2589-5370(21)00299-6/fulltext#seccesectitle0027">最</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2805540">常见</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bmjopen.bmj.com/content/13/6/e069217">最</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9383197/">严重的</a>症状之一，也是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://batemanhornecenter.org/education/me-cfs/">肌痛性脑脊髓炎</a>（也称为慢性疲劳综合症或 ME/CFS）等类似慢性疾病的特征。但在这些疾病中，疲劳与日常疲倦截然不同，以至于与我交谈过的大多数人都没有预料到疲劳的严重性、多方面性和持久性。<br><br>首先，这种疲劳并不是一个单一的症状；而是一种症状。它<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4852700/">有很多面孔</a>。它会让身体变得沉重：丽莎·盖斯勒将其比作“在一个重力极高的星球上穿着铅外骨骼，同时患有严重的关节炎”。它可以使身体加速：许多疲劳的人感到“疲惫不堪”，尽管已经完全精疲力竭，但矛盾的是，他们处于“战斗或逃跑”模式。它可能是认知性的：思想变得迟缓、语无伦次，有时甚至令人痛苦——就像“我的额叶里卡着钢丝绒”，ME 的文学历史学家格温·杜雅尔丁 (Gwynn Dujardin) 告诉我。<br><br>米斯科说，疲劳将最平凡的任务变成了“痛苦的成本效益分析”。如果您洗衣服，您需要休息多长时间才能做饭？如果你喝了水，你能去厕所吗？只有四分之一的长途运输者出现<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/covid19/pulse/long-covid.htm">严重限制其日常活动的</a>症状，但即使是那些患有“中度”病例的人也受到严重限制。斯克里普斯研究中心的项目主管朱莉娅·摩尔·沃格尔仍在工作，但她告诉我，洗头会让她像以前长跑一样疲惫不堪。<br><br>虽然正常的疲劳是暂时的并且可以自行调节——即使在跑完马拉松之后，你也可以自己洗个澡，睡觉后你会感觉更好——但休息通常无法治愈长期新冠肺炎或 ME/CFS 带来的疲劳。 “我醒来时感到很疲惫，”长期感染新冠病毒的莱蒂西亚·苏亚雷斯告诉我。<br><br>由于长期患有新冠肺炎、ME/CFS 和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://chronicillnessinclusion.org.uk/2021/04/28/what-are-energy-impairment-and-elci/">其他限制能量的慢性疾病</a>，仅在美国就有数百万人经历着令人衰弱的疲劳。但美国社会倾向于将无所作为等同于不道德，将生产力等同于价值。面对一种根本不允许人们活动的情况——即使是一种可以测量和解释的缺陷——许多医生和亲人默认不相信。当苏亚雷斯告诉别人她的病时，他们通常会说：“哦，是的，我也累了。”当她卧床数天时，人们告诉她，“我需要这样的周末。”苏亚雷斯的问题是非常现实的，尽管研究人员已经开始弄清楚为什么这么多像她这样的人正在遭受痛苦，但他们还不知道如何阻止它。<br><br>疲劳会产生一种残疾的背景嗡嗡声，但它可能会被更严重的撞击事件所打断，这些事件甚至会剥夺长途运输者通常拥有的少量能量。<br><br>达莉亚·奥勒 (Daria Oller) 是一名物理治疗师和运动教练，因此当她在 2020 年 3 月感染新冠病毒时，她很自然地尝试通过锻炼来改善健康。她不明白为什么在短短的跑步之后，她的疲劳、脑雾、胸痛和其他症状就会急剧加剧，以至于她几乎无法动弹或说话。这些事故与她在训练中学到的一切相矛盾。在与 ME/CFS 的物理治疗师交谈后，她才意识到这种现象有一个名字：<em>劳累后不适</em>。<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://me-pedia.org/wiki/Post-exertional_malaise">劳累后不适</a>(PEM) 是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mayoclinicproceedings.org/article/S0025-6196(21)00513-9/fulltext#secsectitle0030">ME/CFS 的典型特征</a>，也是长期新冠肺炎 (COVID-19) 的共同特征。它通常被描述为一种极端形式的疲劳，但更正确的理解是，它是一种生理状态，在这种状态下，<em>所有</em>现有症状都会更加剧烈地燃烧，并且会引发新的症状。除了疲劳之外，患有 PEM 的人还可能会感到剧烈的放射痛、炎症烧灼感或胃肠道和认知问题：“你会感到中毒、流感样、脑震荡，”米斯科说。疲劳通常在劳累后立即出现，而 PEM 可能会在数小时或数天后出现，而且严重程度不成比例。即使是轻微的体力或脑力劳动也可能会让人们疲惫数天、数周、数月。看医生可能会导致车祸，填写残疾福利申请或感知明亮的灯光和响亮的声音、在炎热的天气里调节体温或应对压力也可能会导致事故。如果您在疲劳时感觉电池电量耗尽，那么在 PEM 中它们就会完全消失。这是可能性的毁灭：大多数人只能在噩梦中经历无法动弹的绝望，杜雅尔丹告诉我。 “PEM 就是这样，但更痛苦。”<br><br>医疗专业人员在培训期间通常不会了解 PEM。许多人怀疑它的存在，因为它与健康人所忍受的任何东西都非常不同。玛丽·迪莫克告诉我，只有当她看到患有 ME/CFS 的儿子马修在她眼前崩溃时，她才明白这意味着什么。 “他简直<em>融化了</em>，”迪莫克说。但大多数人从来没有看到过这样的损害，因为 PEM 将那些处于其中的人隐藏起来，不让公众看到。而且由于它通常会在延迟后发生，经历过 PEM 的人可能会在朋友和同事眼中表现良好，而他们随后不会看到他们后来付出的高昂代价。<br><br>这个价格既真实又可衡量。在心肺运动测试（CPET）中，患者使用跑步机或健身自行车，而医生则记录他们的耗氧量、血压和心率。伊萨卡学院的运动生理学家贝特西·凯勒告诉我，如果一天后重新测试，大多数人都可以重复他们的表现，即使他们患有心脏病或因缺乏活动而身体状况不佳。获得 PEM 的人不能。<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4004422/">第二次的结果是如此不同，以至于</a>当凯勒在 2003 年第一次对某人进行 ME/CFS 测试时，“我告诉我的同事，我们的设备没有校准，”她说。但她和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://content.iospress.com/articles/work/wor203170">其他人</a>在数百名 ME/CFS 和长期感染新冠病毒的患者身上发现了同样的模式——“无法用任何心理学解释的客观结果，”布莱根妇女医院的肺科医生 David Systrom 告诉我。 “许多患者被告知这一切都在他们的脑海中，但这确实掩盖了这一点。”尽管如此，许多保险公司拒绝支付第二次检查的费用，而且许多患者无法在不严重危及健康的情况下进行两次（甚至一次）CPET。 “20 年后，我仍然有医生反驳和忽视客观数据，”凯勒说。 （一些长期的新冠肺炎研究<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.acpjournals.org/doi/full/10.7326/M22-1492">完全忽略了 PEM</a> ，或者将其与疲劳捆绑在一起。）<br><br>奥勒认为，这种忽视的出现是因为 PEM 颠覆了运动有益的教条——对于大多数其他疾病来说，这句格言是正确的。 “改变你整个职业生涯所做的事情并不容易，即使我告诉某人他们可能会伤害病人，”她说。事实上，许多长途运输者的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mdpi.com/1660-4601/19/9/5093">情况变得更糟</a>，因为他们在生病的最初几周<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0264331">没有得到足够的休息</a>，或者试图按照医生的指示进行锻炼来缓解症状。<br><br> PEM 患者也经常被误诊。他们被告知，由于久坐不动，他们的身体状况不佳，而他们的不活动是频繁发生车祸的结果，而不是原因。他们被告知，当他们通常拼命想要移动但要么身体无法移动，要么使用约束来避免撞车时，他们会感到沮丧和没有动力。奥勒是一个由 1,500 名患有长期新冠肺炎的耐力运动员组成的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.facebook.com/groups/longcovidsupportforenduranceathletes/">支持小组</a>的一员，他们非常习惯在疼痛和疲劳中跑步、游泳和骑自行车。 “为什么我们都要<em>停下来</em>？”她问。<br><br>一些患有能量限制性疾病的患者认为，他们的疾病名称和症状使他们更容易被抹黑。<em>疲劳</em>会促使人们尽量减少日常疲劳等严重消耗。<em>慢性疲劳综合症</em>将广泛的致残状况分解为容易被忽视的单一症状。这些抱怨是有道理的，但问题比任何名字都更深刻。<br><br>杜雅尔丁（Dujardin）这位英国教授正在（非常缓慢地）撰写一部疲劳文化史，他认为我们对疲劳的概念已经被几个世纪的还原论所削弱。随着医学研究慢慢分裂成解剖学专业，它失去了对人体能量贡献系统的总体认识，或者说它的缺失。能量的概念曾经是（现在仍然是）万物有灵论哲学的核心，虽然也曾经是西方世界的核心，但现在它在文化上与庸医和伪科学联系在一起。杜雅尔丁说：“美国的每台收银机上都备有小瓶‘能量助推器’，”但当美国国立卫生研究院 (NIH) 于 2021 年召开<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://neuroscienceblueprint.nih.gov/about/events/beyond-symptom-biology-fatigue">疲劳生物学</a>会议时，“专家们不断观察到，疲劳没有标准定义，每个人都认为疲劳没有标准定义。”是从不同的人类能量理念出发进行工作的。”这些术语已经变得如此不具体，毫无帮助，以至于我们的“疲劳”概念可以涵盖多种状态，包括 PEM 和闲置，并且可能受到社会力量的严重影响，尤其是利用他人能量的愿望。<br><br>正如历史学家艾米丽·K·阿贝尔 (Emily K. Abel) 在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/sick-and-tired-an-intimate-history-of-fatigue-emily-k-abel/9781469663340?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《生病与疲倦：疲劳的亲密历史》一书中</em></a>指出的那样，20 世纪之交的许多关于日常疲劳的研究都集中在体力劳动者的疲倦上，并致力于找到让这些工人更加疲劳的方法。富有成效。在此期间，疲劳从雇主必须解决的生理极限转变为个人必须克服的心理失败。 “当今社会对那些不<em>坚持到底</em>的人进行污蔑；<em>坚持下去</em>；<em>表现出勇气</em>，”杜雅尔丁说，而由于颠覆这些规范的罪过，长途运输者“不仅不被相信，而且受到公开的蔑视。”倡导组织 MEAction 的科学和医疗外展主任 Jaime Seltzer 告诉我，疲劳是“彻底反资本主义的”。<br><br>能量限制性疾病对女性的影响也不成比例，长期以来，女性一直被认为是懒惰的人。杜雅尔丹指出，在西方史诗中，像喀耳刻和狄多这样的女性因为用休息的诱惑避开奥德修斯和埃涅阿斯这样的探险英雄而受到严厉的对待。后来，工业化的开始使女性成为居家闲散的象征，而男性却在公共场合劳作。当逃避工作成为一种道德失败时，它也仍然是一种女性的失败。<br><br>这些态度在连续两任美国总统处理新冠疫情的方式中显而易见。唐纳德·特朗普总是表现出男性力量的讽刺，并斥责竞争对手“精力不足”， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/10/trump-strength-coronavirus/616682/">他将自己从冠状病毒中康复描述为一种统治行为</a>。乔·拜登没有那么夸夸其谈，但他仍然明显<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/POTUS/status/1553451657748512768">向公众保证</a>，他正在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/world/us/biden-tests-positive-covid-will-continue-work-white-house-2022-07-21/">努力应对新冠病毒感染</a>，而他的政府则优先考虑让人们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/joe-biden-coronavirus-pandemic-health-emergency-management-federal-emergency-management-agency-20f1e637f03f400376e7381df5ccdb51">重返工作岗位的</a>政策。两人都没有提到可能会导致疲劳或需要休息。<br><br>医学也吸收了社会对疲劳的耻辱，甚至在选择那些加入医学行列的人时也是如此。其众所周知的艰苦训练计划将大多数患有能量限制性疾病的人排除在外，同时重视严重耗尽时的运作能力。这一点，再加上对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/wellness/interactive/2022/women-pain-gender-bias-doctors/">女性疼痛进行心理分析的</a>倾向，有助于解释为什么如此多的长途运输者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/11/health-care-workers-long-covid-are-being-dismissed/620801/">——甚至是那些拥有医学资格的人</a>，如米斯科和奥勒——受到他们寻求护理的专业人士的如此恶劣的对待。她告诉我，当杜雅尔丁第一次因 ME/CFS 症状寻求医疗帮助时，这位十年来一直对她很好的医生突然变得僵硬和多疑，将她所有的详细描述简化为“疲劳”，然后就离开了房间。提供诊断或治疗。<em>永不停息</em>​​的文化压力如此之大，以至于许多人无法接受他们的患者或同龄人可能被迫这样做。<br><br>没有一个大统一的理论可以解释有关长期新冠肺炎和 ME/CFS 的一切，但这些疾病<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41579-022-00846-2">也不是</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mayoclinicproceedings.org/article/S0025-6196(21)00513-9/fulltext#secsectitle0030">完全的谜团</a>。事实上，有大量证据表明至少有两种途径可以解释为什么患有这些疾病的人的能量如此有限。<br><br>首先，大多数患有能量限制性慢性病的人的自主神经系统都存在问题，该系统控制着心跳、呼吸、睡眠、激素释放和其他我们无意识控制的身体功能。当<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9639503/">这个系统</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://academic.oup.com/qjmed/article/100/8/519/1521818">被破坏</a>时——一种称为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.dysautonomiainternational.org/page.php?ID=34">自主神经失调</a>”的情况——肾上腺素等激素可能会在不适当的时刻释放，导致紧张但疲倦的感觉。人们可能会突然感到困倦，就好像他们正在关闭一样。血管可能不会在需要的时候扩张， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.healthrising.org/blog/2021/11/19/heart-failure-muscles-long-covid-chronic-fatigue/">从而剥夺活跃的肌肉和器官的氧气和燃料</a>；这些器官可能包括大脑，导致认知功能障碍，例如<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2022/09/long-covid-brain-fog-symptom-executive-function/671393/">脑雾</a>。<br><br>其次，许多长期患有新冠肺炎和 ME/CFS 的人在产生能量方面存在问题。当病毒侵入人体时，免疫系统会反击，引发炎症状态。感染和炎症都会<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36355108/">损害</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32327453/">线粒体</a>——为细胞提供能量的豆形电池。线粒体功能障碍会产生<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8403932/">称为“活性氧”（ROS）的剧烈化学物质</a>，从而造成更多的细胞损伤。炎症<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ij.hapres.com/htmls/IJ_1341_Detail.html">还会引发新陈代谢转向</a>快速但低效的能量产生方式，耗尽细胞的燃料并充满乳酸。约翰·霍普金斯大学的药理学家和神经科学家宾杜·保罗告诉我，这些变化共同解释了普遍存在的疲劳感，因为“身体难以产生能量”。他们还可以解释患者在细胞充满乳酸和活性氧时所经历的灼热、中毒的感觉。<br><br>这两条途径——自主神经和代谢——也可能是 PEM 的原因。正常情况下，自主神经系统会平稳地调至一种激烈的战斗和逃跑模式，然后调至一种较平静的休息和消化模式。但“在自主神经功能障碍中，旋钮就变成了一个开关，”西奈山的神经科学家和康复专家大卫·普特里诺告诉我。 “你从坐着到站着，你的身体会想：<em>哦，我们要去打猎吗</em>？你停下来，你的身体就会停止运转。”持续的新陈代谢漩涡使这些戏剧性的、不稳定的人字拖变得更加疲惫。受损的线粒体、破坏性的 ROS、低效的新陈代谢和慢性炎症都相互复合，形成恶性循环，如果其变得足够严重，可能会表现为 PEM 崩溃。 “没有人完全确定 PEM 的病因，”Seltzer 告诉我，但“你的新陈代谢发生了巨大的变化，你的神经系统无法恢复平稳”，这是有道理的。普特里诺说，如果人们坚持下去，加深对已经无法满足的身体的代谢需求，那么这个循环就会旋转得更快，“导致渐进性残疾”。<br><br>其他因素也可能在起作用。与健康人相比，长期患有新冠肺炎和 ME/CFS 的人的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thelancet.com/journals/eclinm/article/PIIS2589-5370(23)00051-2/fulltext">大脑</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4032274/">区域</a>的大小、结构或功能存在差异， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.healthrising.org/blog/2018/12/12/death-chronic-fatigue-syndrome-me-cfs-autopsy-files/">包括</a>传递运动信号和调节意识的丘脑，以及控制运动并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/srep21386#:~:text=Hence%2C%20dysfunctions%20of%20the%20basal,thalamic%E2%80%93frontal%20cortical%20system8.">受到影响的</a>基底神经节。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/srep21386#:~:text=Hence%2C%20dysfunctions%20of%20the%20basal,thalamic%E2%80%93frontal%20cortical%20system8.">在疲劳中</a>。长途运输者还存在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8938726/">血管</a>、<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34087216/">红细胞</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-022-02286-7">凝血</a>方面的问题，所有这些都可能进一步阻碍他们的血液、氧气和营养物质的流动。 “这些年来我测试了很多这样的人，我们一次又一次地看到，当系统开始出现故障时，他们都会以同样的方式出现故障，”凯勒说。这些问题共同解释了为什么长期新冠肺炎和 ME/CFS 会出现如此令人眼花缭乱的不同症状。这种多样性让人难以置信——一种疾病<em>怎么</em><em>会导致这一切</em>？——但如果像新陈代谢这样的基本事物出了差错，这正是你所期望的。<br><br>长途运输者可能不知道其症状的生化细节，但他们非常擅长通过隐喻捕捉这些基础。患有自主神经血流问题的人可能会抱怨感觉“被耗尽”，而这种情况确实正在发生：在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.dysautonomiainternational.org/page.php?ID=30">POTS</a> （一种自主神经功能障碍的形式）中，当人们站立时，血液会在下半身积聚。遇到代谢问题的人经常用电池没电来比喻，事实上他们的细胞电池——线粒体——正在受损：“真的感觉细胞水平出了问题，”奥勒告诉我。杜雅尔丁说，细心的医生可以在通常被称为“夸张或夸张”的描述中找到有关患者疾病基础的重要线索。<br><br>一些新冠肺炎长途运输者确实康复了。但一些研究发现，到目前为止， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4505315">大多数人并没有</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-022-29513-z">完全恢复</a>到之前的基线，而且许多病情严重的人仍保持这种状态。这群长期患病的人现在陷入了长期困扰那些患有 ME/CFS 等疾病的人们同样的忽视之中。对此类疾病的研究资金<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32568148/">严重不足</a>，因此不存在治愈方法。在美国，很少有医生<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2022/09/mecfs-chronic-fatigue-syndrome-doctors-long-covid/671518/">知道如何治疗这些疾病</a>，而且许多医生都已接近退休，因此患者很难找到治疗方法。长期新冠肺炎诊所虽然存在，但质量参差不齐：有些诊所对其他能量限制疾病一无所知，但仍然开出可能有害且<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.statnews.com/2017/09/25/chronic-fatigue-syndrome-cdc/">官方不鼓励的治疗方法</a>，例如运动。更了解这些疾病的临床医生知道谨慎至关重要。当 Putrino 与长途运输者一起修复他们的自主神经系统时，他总是尽可能温和地开始，以避免触发 PEM。他说，这样的工作“并不容易，也不是很快”，而且通常意味着稳定人们的情绪，而不是治愈他们。<br><br>稳定可以改变生活，特别是当它涉及患者可以在家中保持的变化时。辅酶 Q10 等<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37432282/">非处方补充剂</a>可以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25386668/">减轻疲劳</a>，线粒体利用辅酶 Q10 产生能量，但<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20010505/">在 ME/CFS 患者中会耗尽</a>。<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://me-pedia.org/wiki/Low_dose_naltrexone">低剂量纳曲酮</a>等抗炎药物可能有一些希望。睡眠卫生可能无法治愈疲劳，但肯定可以减轻疲劳。饮食习惯的改变可能会有所帮助，但正确的改变可能会违反直觉：高纤维食物需要更多的能量来消化，一些长途运输者在吃了<em>看似</em>健康的饭菜后会出现 PEM 发作。这个投资组合中最重要的部分是“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://me-pedia.org/wiki/Pacing#The_principles_of_pacing">节奏</a>”——一种小心地将你的活动水平保持在导致严重崩溃的阈值以下的策略。<br><br>节奏比听起来更具挑战性。练习者不能依赖固定的常规；相反，他们必须学会实时测量自己波动的能量水平，同时敏锐地意识到 PEM 触发因素。一些人转向心率监测器等可穿戴技术，超过 30,000 人正在测试一款<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.makevisible.com/blog/why-we-are-building-visible">名为 Visible 的患者设计应用程序</a>，以帮助发现他们的疾病模式。这些数据很有用，但休息和 PEM 之间的差异可能只是每分钟多 10 或 20 次心跳——长途运输者必须把自己的生命挤进一个狭窄的缝隙。这样做可能会令人沮丧，因为节奏并不是一种恢复策略；而是一种恢复策略。这主要是为了防止情况变得更糟，这使得它的价值更难被欣赏。它对身体的好处是以精神为代价的：散步、锻炼、社交，“我以前为心理健康所做的所有事情都是巨大的能量消耗，”沃格尔告诉我。如果没有经济稳定或社会支持，许多长途运输者就必须工作、养育孩子并照顾自己，即使他们知道自己以后会受苦。 “不过度是不可能的，因为生活就是生活，”沃格尔说。<br><br> “我们的社会不适合节奏，”奥勒补充道。长途运输者必须顶住巨大的文化压力，通过尽最大努力证明自己的价值。他们必须容忍因试图避免事故而受到的惩罚，以及如果失败则得不到信任。 “人们能说的最具侮辱性的话之一就是‘对抗你的疾病’，”米斯科说。这对她来说会容易得多。 “需要很大的自制力和力量才能少做、少做、把你的生活缩小到一两件小事，你试图从中获取快乐才能生存。”对于她和其他许多人来说，休息既是一种医疗必需品，也是一种激进的反抗行为——这种行为本身就令人筋疲力尽。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/07/chronic-fatigue-long-covid-symptoms/674834/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/07/chronic-fatigue-long-covid-symptoms/674834/</item></channel></rss>